WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.996 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.996 --> 00:00:03.493 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.493 --> 00:00:05.988 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.988 --> 00:00:11.427 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.427 --> 00:00:13.760 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So the first
thing I promised to do today

00:00:13.760 --> 00:00:16.920 align:middle line:84%
was to do the last problem on
the first problem set with you

00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:17.760 align:middle line:90%
all.

00:00:17.760 --> 00:00:21.960 align:middle line:84%
And so for context, this was
a pretty difficult problem

00:00:21.960 --> 00:00:25.960 align:middle line:84%
and a lot of people
didn't get it fully right

00:00:25.960 --> 00:00:27.095 align:middle line:90%
or made a mistake.

00:00:27.095 --> 00:00:29.220 align:middle line:84%
And actually, even the
people who did get it right,

00:00:29.220 --> 00:00:31.080 align:middle line:84%
they tended to write
something that was

00:00:31.080 --> 00:00:34.280 align:middle line:90%
pretty long and complicated.

00:00:34.280 --> 00:00:36.140 align:middle line:84%
So I spent a while
thinking about it.

00:00:36.140 --> 00:00:37.800 align:middle line:84%
I think I could have
set up the problem

00:00:37.800 --> 00:00:39.680 align:middle line:90%
with a little more direction.

00:00:39.680 --> 00:00:40.260 align:middle line:90%
But anyway.

00:00:40.260 --> 00:00:43.760 align:middle line:84%
But I will explain
it to everybody

00:00:43.760 --> 00:00:46.680 align:middle line:84%
and try to say what
were the issues

00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:51.120 align:middle line:84%
and what do you need to
know to do it cleanly.

00:00:51.120 --> 00:00:51.940 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:00:51.940 --> 00:00:54.340 align:middle line:84%
So the background
of this problem

00:00:54.340 --> 00:00:55.840 align:middle line:84%
is that we had done
a bunch of stuff

00:00:55.840 --> 00:01:00.070 align:middle line:84%
in class about lines in
the plane, say, an Fq2.

00:01:00.070 --> 00:01:02.590 align:middle line:84%
And the problem was to try to
do something similar for lines

00:01:02.590 --> 00:01:05.390 align:middle line:84%
in Fq3, but it is a
little more complicated.

00:01:05.390 --> 00:01:08.582 align:middle line:84%
So let me first remind everybody
what we did for lines in Fq2,

00:01:08.582 --> 00:01:10.290 align:middle line:84%
and then we'll go up
to three dimensions.

00:01:10.290 --> 00:01:16.476 align:middle line:90%


00:01:16.476 --> 00:01:16.976 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:01:16.976 --> 00:01:20.420 align:middle line:90%
So general setup.

00:01:20.420 --> 00:01:23.790 align:middle line:90%


00:01:23.790 --> 00:01:30.070 align:middle line:84%
So first of all, if we have
a function on Fqd, then f0

00:01:30.070 --> 00:01:32.670 align:middle line:90%
will be the constant part.

00:01:32.670 --> 00:01:41.510 align:middle line:84%
So f0 of x is 1 over q to the d
sum y in Fq to the d of f of y.

00:01:41.510 --> 00:01:44.430 align:middle line:84%
And then f sub h f high
will be the rest of it.

00:01:44.430 --> 00:01:46.570 align:middle line:90%
So f is f0 plus 1.

00:01:46.570 --> 00:01:49.910 align:middle line:90%


00:01:49.910 --> 00:01:52.240 align:middle line:90%
Oh.

00:01:52.240 --> 00:01:54.970 align:middle line:84%
So first we studied
lines in Fq2.

00:01:54.970 --> 00:01:59.290 align:middle line:84%
And this is just going to be a
recap of what we did in class.

00:01:59.290 --> 00:02:01.730 align:middle line:90%
So we noticed.

00:02:01.730 --> 00:02:06.450 align:middle line:84%
So let's say that L1
and L2 are our lines

00:02:06.450 --> 00:02:09.410 align:middle line:84%
or characteristic
function of lines.

00:02:09.410 --> 00:02:11.530 align:middle line:90%
OK, so there are two cases.

00:02:11.530 --> 00:02:17.330 align:middle line:84%
If L1 and L2 are
parallel, then you

00:02:17.330 --> 00:02:19.970 align:middle line:84%
can easily see that their
inner product is zero.

00:02:19.970 --> 00:02:21.790 align:middle line:84%
Parallel means they
don't intersect.

00:02:21.790 --> 00:02:24.490 align:middle line:90%


00:02:24.490 --> 00:02:26.650 align:middle line:90%
So you get this.

00:02:26.650 --> 00:02:27.150 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:27.150 --> 00:02:28.910 align:middle line:84%
And you could also
look at the high part.

00:02:28.910 --> 00:02:31.750 align:middle line:84%
And if you look at the high
part, it will be negative.

00:02:31.750 --> 00:02:36.810 align:middle line:84%
The inner product will
be negative L1 h2h will

00:02:36.810 --> 00:02:40.890 align:middle line:90%
be negative.

00:02:40.890 --> 00:02:42.205 align:middle line:90%
It's easy to compute.

00:02:42.205 --> 00:02:43.830 align:middle line:84%
There's something I
could say out loud.

00:02:43.830 --> 00:02:46.890 align:middle line:90%


00:02:46.890 --> 00:02:56.640 align:middle line:84%
One always has that fg
is f0 g0 plus f high g.

00:02:56.640 --> 00:02:58.640 align:middle line:84%
You can see that from the
Fourier representation

00:02:58.640 --> 00:03:00.160 align:middle line:90%
of these things.

00:03:00.160 --> 00:03:07.000 align:middle line:84%
So in this case, the inner
product of L1 and L2 is 0.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.320 align:middle line:84%
L1 0 and L2 0 are both
positive so their inner product

00:03:10.320 --> 00:03:11.440 align:middle line:90%
is positive.

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:13.720 align:middle line:84%
So for this all to fit
together, this inner product

00:03:13.720 --> 00:03:16.480 align:middle line:90%
should be negative.

00:03:16.480 --> 00:03:19.480 align:middle line:84%
So that's what happens
if they're parallel.

00:03:19.480 --> 00:03:22.560 align:middle line:84%
Now at the time, parallel
felt a special case.

00:03:22.560 --> 00:03:24.260 align:middle line:84%
Two lines are
usually not parallel.

00:03:24.260 --> 00:03:25.780 align:middle line:84%
Once in a while
they're parallel.

00:03:25.780 --> 00:03:30.040 align:middle line:84%
So maybe the more important
case is if they're not parallel.

00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:34.960 align:middle line:90%
L1 and L2 are not parallel.

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:37.520 align:middle line:84%
So if they're not parallel,
then they intersect.

00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:43.320 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, the sum
L1 of x, L2 of x is 1.

00:03:43.320 --> 00:03:51.020 align:middle line:84%
But if you take the high
part, L1h, L2h, you get 0.

00:03:51.020 --> 00:03:54.350 align:middle line:84%
So the high parts
are orthogonal.

00:03:54.350 --> 00:03:55.030 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:55.030 --> 00:03:58.190 align:middle line:84%
And we discussed a couple
of ways of seeing this.

00:03:58.190 --> 00:04:04.910 align:middle line:84%
So one way to see it is based
on the Fourier transform.

00:04:04.910 --> 00:04:10.310 align:middle line:84%
So if you take L
hat of ksi, its norm

00:04:10.310 --> 00:04:16.670 align:middle line:84%
is q times characteristic
function of L perp.

00:04:16.670 --> 00:04:21.630 align:middle line:84%
And so in particular,
the support

00:04:21.630 --> 00:04:27.430 align:middle line:84%
of L1 hat intersected
with the support of L2 hat

00:04:27.430 --> 00:04:32.030 align:middle line:84%
is L1 perp intersected
with L2 perp, which

00:04:32.030 --> 00:04:38.830 align:middle line:84%
is just the origin if the lines
are in different directions.

00:04:38.830 --> 00:04:42.470 align:middle line:84%
This is all under L1
and L2 are not parallel.

00:04:42.470 --> 00:04:44.750 align:middle line:84%
L1 and L2 are not
parallel, L1 and L2

00:04:44.750 --> 00:04:47.190 align:middle line:84%
hat also are not parallel,
and they intersect only

00:04:47.190 --> 00:04:49.310 align:middle line:90%
at the origin.

00:04:49.310 --> 00:04:53.245 align:middle line:84%
And then by looking at the high
part, we leave out the origin.

00:04:53.245 --> 00:04:55.120 align:middle line:84%
So there's nothing left
where they intersect.

00:04:55.120 --> 00:04:58.060 align:middle line:84%
And that gives us
the orthogonal.

00:04:58.060 --> 00:04:58.560 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:04:58.560 --> 00:05:04.260 align:middle line:84%
So once we had this, we used
it to prove a proposition.

00:05:04.260 --> 00:05:12.540 align:middle line:84%
That said, if f is the sum
over some set of lines of L,

00:05:12.540 --> 00:05:18.260 align:middle line:84%
then f high L2
squared is bounded

00:05:18.260 --> 00:05:27.100 align:middle line:84%
by the sum over the lines of
L high or not high L2 squared,

00:05:27.100 --> 00:05:29.060 align:middle line:84%
which then you could
work out easily

00:05:29.060 --> 00:05:32.340 align:middle line:84%
as bounded by the
number of lines times q.

00:05:32.340 --> 00:05:33.880 align:middle line:90%
This is almost an equality.

00:05:33.880 --> 00:05:36.880 align:middle line:90%


00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:37.380 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:37.380 --> 00:05:40.260 align:middle line:90%


00:05:40.260 --> 00:05:43.220 align:middle line:84%
So this was really
the key thing.

00:05:43.220 --> 00:05:45.120 align:middle line:84%
And this came from
orthogonality.

00:05:45.120 --> 00:05:49.680 align:middle line:84%
You can think of it as taking
this sum and expanding it out.

00:05:49.680 --> 00:05:54.200 align:middle line:84%
So this is the sum
L1 and L2 in our set

00:05:54.200 --> 00:06:00.200 align:middle line:90%
of lines of the sum L1h L2h.

00:06:00.200 --> 00:06:02.700 align:middle line:84%
And for each of these,
we plugged in that.

00:06:02.700 --> 00:06:08.313 align:middle line:90%


00:06:08.313 --> 00:06:08.813 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:08.813 --> 00:06:12.640 align:middle line:84%
So now let's go to three
dimensions, see what's the same

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:15.900 align:middle line:84%
and what's different,
and most importantly,

00:06:15.900 --> 00:06:17.980 align:middle line:84%
what should be the analog
of this proposition.

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:25.940 align:middle line:90%


00:06:25.940 --> 00:06:26.440 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:26.440 --> 00:06:27.520 align:middle line:90%
So lines in Fq3.

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:31.800 align:middle line:90%


00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:35.160 align:middle line:84%
So they could still be
parallel or not parallel.

00:06:35.160 --> 00:06:43.960 align:middle line:84%
So if L1 and L2 are parallel,
then everything is still true.

00:06:43.960 --> 00:06:47.640 align:middle line:84%
They're parallel,
then this is 0.

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:54.110 align:middle line:84%
And if we wanted to take the
high part, it would be negative.

00:06:54.110 --> 00:06:55.970 align:middle line:90%
Just the same as before.

00:06:55.970 --> 00:06:56.470 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:06:56.470 --> 00:06:57.678 align:middle line:90%
What if they're not parallel?

00:06:57.678 --> 00:07:01.670 align:middle line:90%


00:07:01.670 --> 00:07:06.050 align:middle line:84%
If they're not parallel, there
are still two possibilities.

00:07:06.050 --> 00:07:08.750 align:middle line:84%
They could intersect each
other or they could not

00:07:08.750 --> 00:07:11.630 align:middle line:90%
intersect each other.

00:07:11.630 --> 00:07:14.750 align:middle line:90%
So I guess there's subcases.

00:07:14.750 --> 00:07:20.590 align:middle line:84%
If they intersect, then
the sum on X L1, L2

00:07:20.590 --> 00:07:25.070 align:middle line:84%
would be 1,
intersecting one point.

00:07:25.070 --> 00:07:26.950 align:middle line:90%
That looks like before.

00:07:26.950 --> 00:07:28.580 align:middle line:84%
And then we could
take the high part.

00:07:28.580 --> 00:07:33.070 align:middle line:90%


00:07:33.070 --> 00:07:36.430 align:middle line:90%
But the high part isn't 0.

00:07:36.430 --> 00:07:38.490 align:middle line:84%
So this is an important
thing that's different.

00:07:38.490 --> 00:07:41.590 align:middle line:90%


00:07:41.590 --> 00:07:45.270 align:middle line:84%
So one common mistake was not
to do this computation carefully

00:07:45.270 --> 00:07:49.180 align:middle line:84%
and just assume it should be 0
like it was in two dimensions.

00:07:49.180 --> 00:07:50.040 align:middle line:90%
But it's not.

00:07:50.040 --> 00:07:54.100 align:middle line:90%


00:07:54.100 --> 00:07:57.060 align:middle line:84%
There's not that much difference
between 1 and 1 minus 1 over q,

00:07:57.060 --> 00:07:59.780 align:middle line:84%
so it's not clear that we're
accomplishing a whole lot

00:07:59.780 --> 00:08:01.210 align:middle line:90%
by focusing on the high part.

00:08:01.210 --> 00:08:05.580 align:middle line:90%


00:08:05.580 --> 00:08:07.780 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:08:07.780 --> 00:08:09.380 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:09.380 --> 00:08:11.960 align:middle line:84%
So to see this, we could
do this computation.

00:08:11.960 --> 00:08:16.420 align:middle line:84%
It's elementary but it's
a little bit tedious.

00:08:16.420 --> 00:08:18.880 align:middle line:84%
But let me see if I can
say something conceptual.

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:23.300 align:middle line:90%


00:08:23.300 --> 00:08:25.860 align:middle line:84%
So the reason that
this happened here

00:08:25.860 --> 00:08:30.180 align:middle line:84%
is that the two high parts
are independent of each other

00:08:30.180 --> 00:08:30.960 align:middle line:90%
as functions.

00:08:30.960 --> 00:08:35.260 align:middle line:84%
That's a high brow way of
saying what's going on.

00:08:35.260 --> 00:08:38.900 align:middle line:90%
And that's not true anymore.

00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:43.380 align:middle line:84%
If you have two lines that
intersect in three space,

00:08:43.380 --> 00:08:45.610 align:middle line:84%
it's not independent
of each other.

00:08:45.610 --> 00:08:48.202 align:middle line:84%
So if you know that
you're in the first line,

00:08:48.202 --> 00:08:50.410 align:middle line:84%
then you're much more likely
to be in the second line

00:08:50.410 --> 00:08:51.952 align:middle line:84%
than if you were
just a random point.

00:08:51.952 --> 00:08:56.090 align:middle line:90%


00:08:56.090 --> 00:08:57.988 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:57.988 --> 00:09:00.530 align:middle line:84%
I don't know if that's helpful,
but you could also just check

00:09:00.530 --> 00:09:03.510 align:middle line:90%
that that's how it goes.

00:09:03.510 --> 00:09:07.850 align:middle line:90%


00:09:07.850 --> 00:09:10.310 align:middle line:90%
They could also not intersect.

00:09:10.310 --> 00:09:14.330 align:middle line:90%


00:09:14.330 --> 00:09:18.130 align:middle line:84%
If they don't intersect
then everything is the same

00:09:18.130 --> 00:09:19.970 align:middle line:90%
as the parallel case actually.

00:09:19.970 --> 00:09:22.930 align:middle line:90%
So that's going to be 0.

00:09:22.930 --> 00:09:25.652 align:middle line:84%
And the sum of the high
parts, the inner product

00:09:25.652 --> 00:09:27.110 align:middle line:84%
of the high parts
will be negative.

00:09:27.110 --> 00:09:29.420 align:middle line:84%
If you do it carefully,
it's negative 1 over q.

00:09:29.420 --> 00:09:30.670 align:middle line:90%
Same thing would be true here.

00:09:30.670 --> 00:09:37.130 align:middle line:90%


00:09:37.130 --> 00:09:38.330 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:38.330 --> 00:09:42.670 align:middle line:84%
So another direction that
this suggested to some people

00:09:42.670 --> 00:09:45.830 align:middle line:84%
is that we ought to try to
think how many pairs of lines

00:09:45.830 --> 00:09:48.350 align:middle line:84%
intersect, as opposed
to the pairs of lines

00:09:48.350 --> 00:09:50.790 align:middle line:90%
that don't intersect.

00:09:50.790 --> 00:09:53.110 align:middle line:84%
That is a totally
reasonable way of thinking

00:09:53.110 --> 00:09:54.510 align:middle line:90%
about this from the beginning.

00:09:54.510 --> 00:09:58.590 align:middle line:84%
But it's not obvious
how to figure that out.

00:09:58.590 --> 00:10:02.350 align:middle line:84%
It is possible for every
pair of lines to intersect.

00:10:02.350 --> 00:10:05.390 align:middle line:84%
There are two significant
ways that could happen.

00:10:05.390 --> 00:10:08.010 align:middle line:84%
One way is you could take all
the lines through the origin.

00:10:08.010 --> 00:10:10.510 align:middle line:84%
Just pick a point and take all
the lines through that point.

00:10:10.510 --> 00:10:13.230 align:middle line:84%
Then every pair of lines
will intersect at that point,

00:10:13.230 --> 00:10:17.190 align:middle line:90%
have a porcupine shape.

00:10:17.190 --> 00:10:20.310 align:middle line:84%
The second way that almost
all the lines could intersect

00:10:20.310 --> 00:10:22.450 align:middle line:84%
is to choose them
all in a plane.

00:10:22.450 --> 00:10:25.090 align:middle line:84%
So if you fix a plane and then
you choose lines in the plane,

00:10:25.090 --> 00:10:27.790 align:middle line:84%
a few of them might be parallel,
but almost every pair of lines

00:10:27.790 --> 00:10:29.130 align:middle line:90%
in the plane will intersect.

00:10:29.130 --> 00:10:34.870 align:middle line:90%


00:10:34.870 --> 00:10:37.770 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, so people tried to
explore this a little bit,

00:10:37.770 --> 00:10:43.900 align:middle line:84%
but it's not so clear how
to put a bound about how

00:10:43.900 --> 00:10:47.800 align:middle line:90%
many pairs will intersect

00:10:47.800 --> 00:10:48.300 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:10:48.300 --> 00:10:56.580 align:middle line:84%
So then another thought is that
instead of focusing on this,

00:10:56.580 --> 00:10:57.515 align:middle line:90%
we should focus--

00:10:57.515 --> 00:10:59.140 align:middle line:84%
we should look at
the Fourier transform

00:10:59.140 --> 00:11:01.972 align:middle line:84%
and just see what the
Fourier transform tells us.

00:11:01.972 --> 00:11:04.180 align:middle line:84%
So the Fourier transform
does have a nice description

00:11:04.180 --> 00:11:07.120 align:middle line:84%
in any dimension, like you did
on the first part of the problem

00:11:07.120 --> 00:11:07.620 align:middle line:90%
set.

00:11:07.620 --> 00:11:11.280 align:middle line:90%
And it tells us something.

00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:14.620 align:middle line:84%
So let's think about
the Fourier transform.

00:11:14.620 --> 00:11:16.240 align:middle line:90%
The Fourier point of view.

00:11:16.240 --> 00:11:19.620 align:middle line:90%


00:11:19.620 --> 00:11:20.392 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:20.392 --> 00:11:24.020 align:middle line:84%
So if we take the Fourier
transform of our line

00:11:24.020 --> 00:11:25.860 align:middle line:84%
and look at its
absolute value, it

00:11:25.860 --> 00:11:28.780 align:middle line:84%
will be q times the
characteristic function

00:11:28.780 --> 00:11:30.820 align:middle line:90%
of L perp.

00:11:30.820 --> 00:11:33.080 align:middle line:84%
But notice, so the
L is still a line.

00:11:33.080 --> 00:11:37.500 align:middle line:84%
But since we're in
three dimensions,

00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:39.790 align:middle line:90%
L perp is two dimensional.

00:11:39.790 --> 00:11:43.083 align:middle line:90%


00:11:43.083 --> 00:11:43.583 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:11:43.583 --> 00:11:48.690 align:middle line:84%
So then if we were to look at
the-- so if L1 and L2 are not

00:11:48.690 --> 00:11:51.290 align:middle line:90%
parallel.

00:11:51.290 --> 00:11:53.050 align:middle line:90%
Not parallel.

00:11:53.050 --> 00:11:57.410 align:middle line:84%
If I look at the support
of L1 hat intersected

00:11:57.410 --> 00:12:01.610 align:middle line:84%
with the support of
L2 hat, well, that's

00:12:01.610 --> 00:12:07.250 align:middle line:84%
L1 perp intersected
with L2 perp.

00:12:07.250 --> 00:12:09.930 align:middle line:84%
So I have a two plane
and I'm intersecting it

00:12:09.930 --> 00:12:12.210 align:middle line:90%
with a different two plane.

00:12:12.210 --> 00:12:16.610 align:middle line:90%
And that will make a line.

00:12:16.610 --> 00:12:17.430 align:middle line:90%
That's a line.

00:12:17.430 --> 00:12:20.250 align:middle line:90%


00:12:20.250 --> 00:12:20.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:20.790 --> 00:12:24.970 align:middle line:84%
So a third common mistake was
to not do this so carefully

00:12:24.970 --> 00:12:27.743 align:middle line:84%
and think that this
intersection was just zero.

00:12:27.743 --> 00:12:30.410 align:middle line:84%
And if the intersection was just
0, when you take the high part,

00:12:30.410 --> 00:12:32.090 align:middle line:84%
you would get rid
of the 0 and that

00:12:32.090 --> 00:12:35.090 align:middle line:84%
would show that L1 and
L2 were orthogonal,

00:12:35.090 --> 00:12:36.490 align:middle line:90%
which is not actually--

00:12:36.490 --> 00:12:39.420 align:middle line:84%
L1 and L2 hat orthogonal,
which is not actually the case.

00:12:39.420 --> 00:12:42.320 align:middle line:90%


00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:44.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:45.140 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:12:45.140 --> 00:12:47.800 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:12:47.800 --> 00:12:48.580 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:12:48.580 --> 00:12:51.080 align:middle line:84%
So to prove some
kind of an estimate

00:12:51.080 --> 00:12:53.280 align:middle line:84%
about how these lines
intersect, we're

00:12:53.280 --> 00:12:56.840 align:middle line:84%
going to try to combine
this information

00:12:56.840 --> 00:12:58.498 align:middle line:90%
and this information.

00:12:58.498 --> 00:13:00.040 align:middle line:84%
So if they're
parallel, they actually

00:13:00.040 --> 00:13:02.280 align:middle line:84%
are orthogonal,
which is very good.

00:13:02.280 --> 00:13:06.800 align:middle line:84%
If they're not parallel,
they're not fully orthogonal.

00:13:06.800 --> 00:13:09.217 align:middle line:90%
But the Fourier transform of--

00:13:09.217 --> 00:13:10.800 align:middle line:84%
the intersection of
Fourier transforms

00:13:10.800 --> 00:13:12.340 align:middle line:90%
is kind of small and special.

00:13:12.340 --> 00:13:15.200 align:middle line:90%
We'll try to use that.

00:13:15.200 --> 00:13:18.008 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:13:18.008 --> 00:13:20.257 align:middle line:84%
So here's the
analogous proposition.

00:13:20.257 --> 00:13:21.840 align:middle line:84%
And I think it would
have been helpful

00:13:21.840 --> 00:13:24.880 align:middle line:84%
if I had stated this
in the problem set.

00:13:24.880 --> 00:13:27.100 align:middle line:90%
So here's how it goes.

00:13:27.100 --> 00:13:37.220 align:middle line:84%
So if L is a set of lines
in three dimensions in Fq3

00:13:37.220 --> 00:13:49.540 align:middle line:84%
and f is the sum of
these lines, then

00:13:49.540 --> 00:13:53.260 align:middle line:90%
f L2 squared is bounded by--

00:13:53.260 --> 00:13:58.460 align:middle line:84%
so what we had before was
something like orthogonality.

00:13:58.460 --> 00:14:05.660 align:middle line:84%
Some L and L of fL or-- and
this is with the high part.

00:14:05.660 --> 00:14:08.580 align:middle line:90%
The high part L2 squared.

00:14:08.580 --> 00:14:10.240 align:middle line:90%
And that's not true anymore.

00:14:10.240 --> 00:14:13.280 align:middle line:84%
But it is true if we put
an extra factor of q.

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:16.540 align:middle line:90%


00:14:16.540 --> 00:14:17.526 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:17.526 --> 00:14:23.180 align:middle line:84%
And so then that is
around the number of lines

00:14:23.180 --> 00:14:25.120 align:middle line:84%
times each one of
these is around q,

00:14:25.120 --> 00:14:27.520 align:middle line:84%
and there's another factor
of q which is around there.

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:33.610 align:middle line:90%


00:14:33.610 --> 00:14:35.850 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:35.850 --> 00:14:38.330 align:middle line:84%
So if you compare
these, this is like

00:14:38.330 --> 00:14:40.570 align:middle line:90%
an orthogonality proposition.

00:14:40.570 --> 00:14:42.690 align:middle line:84%
This is clearly much
weaker than orthogonality

00:14:42.690 --> 00:14:45.810 align:middle line:84%
because we have a
big factor here.

00:14:45.810 --> 00:14:48.927 align:middle line:84%
Nevertheless, it's
stronger than nothing.

00:14:48.927 --> 00:14:50.510 align:middle line:84%
Even though there's
a big factor here,

00:14:50.510 --> 00:14:53.550 align:middle line:84%
this proposition has some
meaningful information in it.

00:14:53.550 --> 00:14:56.890 align:middle line:90%


00:14:56.890 --> 00:14:57.390 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:14:57.390 --> 00:15:00.810 align:middle line:84%
So let me explain how to
prove this proposition,

00:15:00.810 --> 00:15:03.730 align:middle line:84%
and then we'll
digest it and argue

00:15:03.730 --> 00:15:06.170 align:middle line:84%
that it does tell us
something interesting,

00:15:06.170 --> 00:15:08.490 align:middle line:84%
even though it's a lot
weaker, in some sense,

00:15:08.490 --> 00:15:12.770 align:middle line:84%
than the two
dimensional proposition.

00:15:12.770 --> 00:15:13.542 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:13.542 --> 00:15:15.070 align:middle line:90%
So how do we prove this?

00:15:15.070 --> 00:15:20.570 align:middle line:90%


00:15:20.570 --> 00:15:23.730 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:15:23.730 --> 00:15:30.690 align:middle line:84%
So for parallel lines, we
have really good information.

00:15:30.690 --> 00:15:33.800 align:middle line:84%
So let's first think about all
the lines in a given direction

00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:36.240 align:middle line:90%
and add those up.

00:15:36.240 --> 00:15:40.440 align:middle line:84%
And then after that, we'll add
up the different directions.

00:15:40.440 --> 00:15:43.300 align:middle line:84%
So we'll label the
directions by w.

00:15:43.300 --> 00:15:49.680 align:middle line:84%
So w will be a one dimensional
subspace direction.

00:15:49.680 --> 00:15:54.920 align:middle line:84%
And then Lw will be the
lines in our set of lines

00:15:54.920 --> 00:15:57.290 align:middle line:90%
that are parallel to w.

00:15:57.290 --> 00:16:00.360 align:middle line:90%


00:16:00.360 --> 00:16:03.160 align:middle line:90%
And we can also make an fw.

00:16:03.160 --> 00:16:07.840 align:middle line:84%
That's the sum over
the lines in Lw of L.

00:16:07.840 --> 00:16:11.600 align:middle line:84%
So f itself is the sum of the
different directions of fw.

00:16:11.600 --> 00:16:16.612 align:middle line:90%


00:16:16.612 --> 00:16:21.000 align:middle line:84%
So the first thing that we'll
do is prove some estimates

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:24.080 align:middle line:90%
about fw.

00:16:24.080 --> 00:16:26.320 align:middle line:84%
And this part really
is not that difficult.

00:16:26.320 --> 00:16:28.940 align:middle line:84%
We're adding up functions
with disjoint supports.

00:16:28.940 --> 00:16:32.550 align:middle line:84%
It's not that
complicated, what happens.

00:16:32.550 --> 00:16:33.990 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:16:33.990 --> 00:16:40.570 align:middle line:84%
So fw L2 squared
is the size of w.

00:16:40.570 --> 00:16:41.070 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:16:41.070 --> 00:16:47.830 align:middle line:90%
The size of Lw times q.

00:16:47.830 --> 00:16:48.690 align:middle line:90%
Why is that?

00:16:48.690 --> 00:16:52.710 align:middle line:90%


00:16:52.710 --> 00:16:55.440 align:middle line:90%
Because the-- so proof.

00:16:55.440 --> 00:16:58.150 align:middle line:90%


00:16:58.150 --> 00:17:11.349 align:middle line:84%
So sum fw squared is the sum L
and Lw sum on x L of x squared.

00:17:11.349 --> 00:17:12.770 align:middle line:90%
But these lines are parallel.

00:17:12.770 --> 00:17:14.589 align:middle line:84%
They're disjoint
from each other.

00:17:14.589 --> 00:17:18.390 align:middle line:84%
So there's only-- at any
given x, only one of them

00:17:18.390 --> 00:17:21.270 align:middle line:90%
is making an appearance.

00:17:21.270 --> 00:17:27.819 align:middle line:84%
So this is sum L and L
sum on x out of x squared.

00:17:27.819 --> 00:17:32.810 align:middle line:90%


00:17:32.810 --> 00:17:34.590 align:middle line:84%
And then that's the
right-hand side.

00:17:34.590 --> 00:17:39.190 align:middle line:90%


00:17:39.190 --> 00:17:40.690 align:middle line:84%
It's not clear yet
why we would want

00:17:40.690 --> 00:17:42.773 align:middle line:84%
to look at the high frequency
part, but if we did,

00:17:42.773 --> 00:17:44.290 align:middle line:90%
it wouldn't change much.

00:17:44.290 --> 00:17:51.930 align:middle line:84%
So fw high, L2 squared is
less than fw L2 squared.

00:17:51.930 --> 00:17:55.020 align:middle line:84%
And so the proof is that this
is true for any function.

00:17:55.020 --> 00:17:58.890 align:middle line:90%


00:17:58.890 --> 00:18:03.490 align:middle line:90%
We have it over there.

00:18:03.490 --> 00:18:09.770 align:middle line:84%
For any function gL2 squared
is always g0 L2 squared plus g

00:18:09.770 --> 00:18:13.210 align:middle line:90%
high L2 squared.

00:18:13.210 --> 00:18:16.120 align:middle line:84%
So it's at least as big
as g high L2 squared.

00:18:16.120 --> 00:18:19.330 align:middle line:90%


00:18:19.330 --> 00:18:20.470 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:20.470 --> 00:18:23.150 align:middle line:84%
You can do it with
Fourier transform.

00:18:23.150 --> 00:18:24.400 align:middle line:90%
You could also do it by hand.

00:18:24.400 --> 00:18:28.440 align:middle line:90%


00:18:28.440 --> 00:18:31.640 align:middle line:90%
Let's call it an exercise.

00:18:31.640 --> 00:18:34.020 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:18:34.020 --> 00:18:37.600 align:middle line:84%
Now, the more tricky
and interesting point

00:18:37.600 --> 00:18:41.720 align:middle line:84%
is what happens when we add
together the different w.

00:18:41.720 --> 00:18:46.360 align:middle line:84%
And when we do that, the way
their Fourier transforms behave

00:18:46.360 --> 00:18:47.620 align:middle line:90%
will come into play.

00:18:47.620 --> 00:18:53.800 align:middle line:90%


00:18:53.800 --> 00:18:54.620 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:18:54.620 --> 00:18:57.280 align:middle line:90%


00:18:57.280 --> 00:19:00.320 align:middle line:84%
So I guess that
this is lemma three.

00:19:00.320 --> 00:19:02.160 align:middle line:84%
But I'm going to put
a star because this

00:19:02.160 --> 00:19:03.300 align:middle line:90%
is the important lemma.

00:19:03.300 --> 00:19:06.520 align:middle line:84%
This is where the interesting
stuff is happening.

00:19:06.520 --> 00:19:07.600 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:07.600 --> 00:19:10.880 align:middle line:84%
Important lemma says
that fL2 squared

00:19:10.880 --> 00:19:17.990 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by q plus 1 times
the sum on w of fw L2 squared.

00:19:17.990 --> 00:19:21.800 align:middle line:90%


00:19:21.800 --> 00:19:22.560 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:22.560 --> 00:19:23.407 align:middle line:90%
Here's the proof.

00:19:23.407 --> 00:19:23.990 align:middle line:90%
Oh, I'm sorry.

00:19:23.990 --> 00:19:26.298 align:middle line:84%
And now I need to
put high everywhere.

00:19:26.298 --> 00:19:31.670 align:middle line:90%


00:19:31.670 --> 00:19:32.830 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:19:32.830 --> 00:19:39.770 align:middle line:84%
So f high L2 squared
is, by Plancherel,

00:19:39.770 --> 00:19:45.820 align:middle line:84%
it's the sum on the nonzero
ksi f hat of ksi squared.

00:19:45.820 --> 00:19:50.990 align:middle line:90%


00:19:50.990 --> 00:19:55.080 align:middle line:84%
So remember that f0 is the
zero frequency part of f.

00:19:55.080 --> 00:19:58.310 align:middle line:84%
f high is all the
other frequencies in f.

00:19:58.310 --> 00:20:00.570 align:middle line:90%
And so this is Plancherel.

00:20:00.570 --> 00:20:04.310 align:middle line:90%


00:20:04.310 --> 00:20:04.810 align:middle line:90%
Oh, OK.

00:20:04.810 --> 00:20:07.105 align:middle line:84%
And I guess because of the
finite field normalization

00:20:07.105 --> 00:20:08.730 align:middle line:84%
that I always have
trouble remembering,

00:20:08.730 --> 00:20:09.605 align:middle line:90%
there should be this.

00:20:09.605 --> 00:20:13.150 align:middle line:90%


00:20:13.150 --> 00:20:13.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:13.870 --> 00:20:17.630 align:middle line:90%
Now, f is the sum of fw.

00:20:17.630 --> 00:20:23.290 align:middle line:84%
This is 1 over q cubed times
the sum and the nonzero ksi,

00:20:23.290 --> 00:20:28.720 align:middle line:84%
sum on w of fw hat
of ksi squared.

00:20:28.720 --> 00:20:38.137 align:middle line:90%


00:20:38.137 --> 00:20:38.637 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:20:38.637 --> 00:20:42.840 align:middle line:90%


00:20:42.840 --> 00:20:44.890 align:middle line:84%
Now, in two dimensions,
we could have done this

00:20:44.890 --> 00:20:46.570 align:middle line:90%
and gotten to this point.

00:20:46.570 --> 00:20:50.570 align:middle line:84%
And then we would have been very
happy because the different fw

00:20:50.570 --> 00:20:53.070 align:middle line:90%
hats have different supports.

00:20:53.070 --> 00:20:56.930 align:middle line:84%
They're supported on different
lines through the origin.

00:20:56.930 --> 00:21:00.293 align:middle line:90%
So we would have orthogonality.

00:21:00.293 --> 00:21:02.210 align:middle line:84%
The way it would have
worked in two dimensions

00:21:02.210 --> 00:21:04.690 align:middle line:84%
is that for any
particular ksi, there

00:21:04.690 --> 00:21:08.970 align:middle line:84%
is only one w which
is nonzero in the sum.

00:21:08.970 --> 00:21:11.660 align:middle line:84%
And so we could take
the square inside.

00:21:11.660 --> 00:21:14.410 align:middle line:90%


00:21:14.410 --> 00:21:15.182 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:21:15.182 --> 00:21:17.490 align:middle line:90%
But that's not true anymore.

00:21:17.490 --> 00:21:22.920 align:middle line:84%
So fw hat is
supported on w perp,

00:21:22.920 --> 00:21:28.560 align:middle line:84%
and in any given
direction, any given ksi,

00:21:28.560 --> 00:21:34.040 align:middle line:84%
there are many different two
planes that contain that ksi.

00:21:34.040 --> 00:21:36.560 align:middle line:90%
So let's write that down.

00:21:36.560 --> 00:21:46.120 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to note that the
support of fw hat is w perp.

00:21:46.120 --> 00:21:57.920 align:middle line:90%
And so for any ksi, the fw--

00:21:57.920 --> 00:22:04.840 align:middle line:84%
the set of w so that f
hat w of ksi is nonzero

00:22:04.840 --> 00:22:10.190 align:middle line:84%
is contained in the set of
w so that w is in ksi perp.

00:22:10.190 --> 00:22:14.860 align:middle line:90%


00:22:14.860 --> 00:22:16.440 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:22:16.440 --> 00:22:20.702 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: We still need
the high part, right?

00:22:20.702 --> 00:22:22.357 align:middle line:90%
On the f hat.

00:22:22.357 --> 00:22:23.190 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:22:23.190 --> 00:22:24.023 align:middle line:90%
So the question is--

00:22:24.023 --> 00:22:26.410 align:middle line:84%
I think the question is--
so on the left-hand side,

00:22:26.410 --> 00:22:27.990 align:middle line:90%
I put the high part of f.

00:22:27.990 --> 00:22:31.150 align:middle line:84%
And the question is, do we
need the high part here?

00:22:31.150 --> 00:22:32.050 align:middle line:90%
Is that the question?

00:22:32.050 --> 00:22:33.050 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Just the zero.

00:22:33.050 --> 00:22:33.908 align:middle line:90%
Not that one.

00:22:33.908 --> 00:22:35.450 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So
we don't need that,

00:22:35.450 --> 00:22:37.790 align:middle line:84%
but I should have
said it clearer.

00:22:37.790 --> 00:22:41.110 align:middle line:84%
So let's all remember that if
you take the high part of f hat

00:22:41.110 --> 00:22:47.070 align:middle line:84%
ksi, what you get is f hat
of ksi if ksi is nonzero

00:22:47.070 --> 00:22:51.250 align:middle line:90%
and zero if ksi is zero.

00:22:51.250 --> 00:22:52.970 align:middle line:90%
This is f high hat.

00:22:52.970 --> 00:22:58.470 align:middle line:90%


00:22:58.470 --> 00:22:58.970 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:22:58.970 --> 00:23:02.430 align:middle line:84%
So for any given
frequency ksi, I only

00:23:02.430 --> 00:23:06.810 align:middle line:84%
need to include the
w's in ksi perp.

00:23:06.810 --> 00:23:09.350 align:middle line:90%


00:23:09.350 --> 00:23:14.870 align:middle line:90%
So actually, I can write this.

00:23:14.870 --> 00:23:16.880 align:middle line:90%
And there aren't as many.

00:23:16.880 --> 00:23:19.180 align:middle line:90%
There's more than one of them.

00:23:19.180 --> 00:23:21.740 align:middle line:84%
But there is a
non-trivial bound how many

00:23:21.740 --> 00:23:23.940 align:middle line:90%
are terms are in this sum.

00:23:23.940 --> 00:23:29.780 align:middle line:90%
So the number of w in ksi perp.

00:23:29.780 --> 00:23:31.000 align:middle line:90%
So this is a two plane.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:33.400 align:middle line:84%
We're talking about how many
lines through the origin

00:23:33.400 --> 00:23:34.700 align:middle line:90%
there are in this two plane.

00:23:34.700 --> 00:23:36.360 align:middle line:90%
That's q plus 1.

00:23:36.360 --> 00:23:43.404 align:middle line:90%


00:23:43.404 --> 00:23:47.200 align:middle line:84%
So there are something like q
squared different w in total.

00:23:47.200 --> 00:23:49.860 align:middle line:84%
But for any given ksi, we're
only including q of them

00:23:49.860 --> 00:23:51.980 align:middle line:90%
in the sum here.

00:23:51.980 --> 00:23:53.500 align:middle line:84%
That's not as good
as orthogonality

00:23:53.500 --> 00:23:56.980 align:middle line:84%
but it actually is
helpful information.

00:23:56.980 --> 00:23:59.180 align:middle line:84%
And the way we can
exploit that information

00:23:59.180 --> 00:24:01.220 align:middle line:90%
is by Cauchy-Schwarzing this.

00:24:01.220 --> 00:24:05.780 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to think of this as
the sum of this thing times 1.

00:24:05.780 --> 00:24:07.360 align:middle line:84%
Of course I didn't
change anything.

00:24:07.360 --> 00:24:09.280 align:middle line:84%
And now I can apply
Cauchy-Schwarz.

00:24:09.280 --> 00:24:12.100 align:middle line:90%


00:24:12.100 --> 00:24:16.440 align:middle line:84%
1 over q cubed sum
over the nonzero ksi.

00:24:16.440 --> 00:24:24.040 align:middle line:84%
The first term will be sum
w in ksi perp f hat of w

00:24:24.040 --> 00:24:25.790 align:middle line:90%
of ksi norm squared.

00:24:25.790 --> 00:24:28.520 align:middle line:90%


00:24:28.520 --> 00:24:34.070 align:middle line:84%
And the second half will be sum
w and ksi perp of 1 squared.

00:24:34.070 --> 00:24:40.480 align:middle line:90%


00:24:40.480 --> 00:24:41.200 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:41.200 --> 00:24:44.680 align:middle line:90%
And this is q plus 1.

00:24:44.680 --> 00:24:47.100 align:middle line:84%
So we bring that
out to the front,

00:24:47.100 --> 00:24:49.320 align:middle line:84%
and after that,
what we have left

00:24:49.320 --> 00:24:53.720 align:middle line:84%
is a sum that just involves
each fw one at a time.

00:24:53.720 --> 00:25:00.220 align:middle line:84%
So it's q plus 1, 1 over q
cubed sum on the nonzero ksi.

00:25:00.220 --> 00:25:03.400 align:middle line:90%


00:25:03.400 --> 00:25:06.800 align:middle line:84%
Actually, I could put-- well,
I'll put the sum on w here.

00:25:06.800 --> 00:25:09.580 align:middle line:90%
fw hat of ksi squared.

00:25:09.580 --> 00:25:11.490 align:middle line:84%
But I can switch the
order of these sums.

00:25:11.490 --> 00:25:14.550 align:middle line:90%


00:25:14.550 --> 00:25:16.950 align:middle line:84%
And now if I
Plancherel back, I have

00:25:16.950 --> 00:25:24.630 align:middle line:84%
q plus 1 times the sum
on w fw high L2 squared.

00:25:24.630 --> 00:25:25.890 align:middle line:90%
And that's the statement.

00:25:25.890 --> 00:25:32.490 align:middle line:90%


00:25:32.490 --> 00:25:32.990 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:25:32.990 --> 00:25:34.180 align:middle line:90%
Any questions or comments?

00:25:34.180 --> 00:25:41.070 align:middle line:90%


00:25:41.070 --> 00:25:43.210 align:middle line:84%
In that case, maybe I
have a question for you.

00:25:43.210 --> 00:25:46.030 align:middle line:90%


00:25:46.030 --> 00:25:49.430 align:middle line:84%
In this proof what was
the purpose of taking out

00:25:49.430 --> 00:25:51.390 align:middle line:90%
the 0 frequency?

00:25:51.390 --> 00:25:53.370 align:middle line:90%
What did we gain by doing that?

00:25:53.370 --> 00:25:57.110 align:middle line:90%


00:25:57.110 --> 00:25:58.590 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:25:58.590 --> 00:26:02.610 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: The zero
frequency is equal to 0

00:26:02.610 --> 00:26:07.910 align:middle line:84%
every plane contains
ksi equal to 0.

00:26:07.910 --> 00:26:11.719 align:middle line:84%
So the output would
be [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:11.719 --> 00:26:12.552 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Good.

00:26:12.552 --> 00:26:13.140 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:26:13.140 --> 00:26:17.820 align:middle line:84%
So the comment is that ksi
equals 0 is special because--

00:26:17.820 --> 00:26:20.930 align:middle line:84%
and when ksi is 0, every
w perp goes through 0.

00:26:20.930 --> 00:26:25.780 align:middle line:90%


00:26:25.780 --> 00:26:30.300 align:middle line:84%
So there are q squared different
w's, and every one of them

00:26:30.300 --> 00:26:32.420 align:middle line:90%
has a contribution at 0.

00:26:32.420 --> 00:26:34.180 align:middle line:84%
So if we wanted to
do Cauchy-Schwarz,

00:26:34.180 --> 00:26:37.940 align:middle line:84%
we would have q
squared terms here.

00:26:37.940 --> 00:26:42.040 align:middle line:84%
But at every other ksi, we have
only q w perps going through it.

00:26:42.040 --> 00:26:44.540 align:middle line:84%
And so we have to
pay only q over here.

00:26:44.540 --> 00:26:46.610 align:middle line:84%
That's what's different
about 0 and not 0.

00:26:46.610 --> 00:26:49.500 align:middle line:90%


00:26:49.500 --> 00:26:52.260 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:26:52.260 --> 00:26:53.610 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:53.610 --> 00:26:55.980 align:middle line:84%
So now the proof of the
proposition over there

00:26:55.980 --> 00:26:58.420 align:middle line:90%
is just assembling these lemmas.

00:26:58.420 --> 00:27:02.060 align:middle line:84%
So the proposition
says that I want

00:27:02.060 --> 00:27:05.580 align:middle line:90%
to bound the L2 norm of f high.

00:27:05.580 --> 00:27:07.500 align:middle line:90%
How do I do it?

00:27:07.500 --> 00:27:09.750 align:middle line:84%
Lemma three says the
L2 norm of f high

00:27:09.750 --> 00:27:13.370 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by q plus 1
times the sum on w of those,

00:27:13.370 --> 00:27:15.370 align:middle line:84%
and lemmas one and
lemmas two tells me

00:27:15.370 --> 00:27:18.250 align:middle line:90%
how big each one of these is.

00:27:18.250 --> 00:27:21.190 align:middle line:84%
If you put that all together,
you get proposition two.

00:27:21.190 --> 00:27:23.870 align:middle line:90%


00:27:23.870 --> 00:27:24.370 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:24.370 --> 00:27:28.290 align:middle line:90%


00:27:28.290 --> 00:27:28.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:28.790 --> 00:27:35.730 align:middle line:90%


00:27:35.730 --> 00:27:36.810 align:middle line:90%
Great.

00:27:36.810 --> 00:27:37.450 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:37.450 --> 00:27:39.570 align:middle line:84%
So now let me erase
this a little bit

00:27:39.570 --> 00:27:42.890 align:middle line:84%
and let's think about what
proposition two tells us

00:27:42.890 --> 00:27:44.420 align:middle line:90%
about lines in three space.

00:27:44.420 --> 00:28:03.530 align:middle line:90%


00:28:03.530 --> 00:28:05.386 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:05.386 --> 00:28:11.630 align:middle line:84%
So actually, let's first review
what proposition one tells us

00:28:11.630 --> 00:28:14.630 align:middle line:90%
about lines in the plane.

00:28:14.630 --> 00:28:18.150 align:middle line:90%
So f is a sum of lines.

00:28:18.150 --> 00:28:24.070 align:middle line:84%
f0 is always the number
of lines divided by q,

00:28:24.070 --> 00:28:28.670 align:middle line:84%
and so f0 L2 squared
works out to be

00:28:28.670 --> 00:28:30.050 align:middle line:90%
the number of lines squared.

00:28:30.050 --> 00:28:32.470 align:middle line:90%
It's not hard to check.

00:28:32.470 --> 00:28:40.310 align:middle line:84%
And proposition one, it tells
us that f high L2 squared

00:28:40.310 --> 00:28:43.430 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by the
number of lines times q.

00:28:43.430 --> 00:28:45.470 align:middle line:84%
So if you put
these together, you

00:28:45.470 --> 00:28:49.950 align:middle line:84%
see that if the number of
lines is much bigger than q,

00:28:49.950 --> 00:28:52.240 align:middle line:90%
then f is mostly constant.

00:28:52.240 --> 00:28:54.990 align:middle line:90%


00:28:54.990 --> 00:29:00.230 align:middle line:84%
So then L2 norm of f
high is much smaller

00:29:00.230 --> 00:29:02.630 align:middle line:84%
than the L2 norm of
the constant part.

00:29:02.630 --> 00:29:04.670 align:middle line:84%
The sum of lines
looks almost constant

00:29:04.670 --> 00:29:08.260 align:middle line:90%
with some small perturbations.

00:29:08.260 --> 00:29:08.860 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:29:08.860 --> 00:29:12.620 align:middle line:84%
What's the analog of
that in three dimensions?

00:29:12.620 --> 00:29:13.860 align:middle line:90%
Lines in Fq3.

00:29:13.860 --> 00:29:20.360 align:middle line:90%


00:29:20.360 --> 00:29:20.860 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:29:20.860 --> 00:29:23.540 align:middle line:84%
So in three dimensions,
f0 is the number

00:29:23.540 --> 00:29:28.780 align:middle line:84%
of lines over q squared because
each line occupies a 1 over q

00:29:28.780 --> 00:29:31.260 align:middle line:90%
squared fraction of space.

00:29:31.260 --> 00:29:35.020 align:middle line:84%
And so then you can compute
the L2 norm of f0 squared.

00:29:35.020 --> 00:29:40.300 align:middle line:84%
It's not difficult. It's
number of lines squared over q.

00:29:40.300 --> 00:29:43.780 align:middle line:84%
And on the other
hand, we know that f

00:29:43.780 --> 00:29:49.820 align:middle line:84%
high L2 squared is at most the
number of lines times q squared.

00:29:49.820 --> 00:29:52.100 align:middle line:90%
So you can put these together.

00:29:52.100 --> 00:29:54.040 align:middle line:84%
If the number of
lines is large enough,

00:29:54.040 --> 00:29:56.863 align:middle line:84%
then this is way
bigger than this.

00:29:56.863 --> 00:29:58.280 align:middle line:84%
If you do a little
bit of algebra,

00:29:58.280 --> 00:30:01.420 align:middle line:84%
you see that if
the number of lines

00:30:01.420 --> 00:30:08.130 align:middle line:84%
is much larger than q cubed,
then the high frequency part

00:30:08.130 --> 00:30:11.330 align:middle line:84%
is much smaller than
the constant part.

00:30:11.330 --> 00:30:14.410 align:middle line:84%
So if you add up more
than q cubed lines

00:30:14.410 --> 00:30:16.170 align:middle line:84%
in three dimensional
space, you'll

00:30:16.170 --> 00:30:17.850 align:middle line:84%
get something that's
mostly constant

00:30:17.850 --> 00:30:21.770 align:middle line:90%
with some small perturbations.

00:30:21.770 --> 00:30:22.730 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:22.730 --> 00:30:27.970 align:middle line:84%
Now these are both the correct
thresholds for this behavior.

00:30:27.970 --> 00:30:28.930 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:30:28.930 --> 00:30:32.810 align:middle line:84%
So in two dimensions suppose
I add up less than q lines,

00:30:32.810 --> 00:30:34.610 align:middle line:90%
say q over two lines.

00:30:34.610 --> 00:30:36.710 align:middle line:84%
Well, they only
fill half of space.

00:30:36.710 --> 00:30:40.130 align:middle line:84%
So there's no way that thing
is going to look constant.

00:30:40.130 --> 00:30:45.010 align:middle line:84%
So this will certainly not be
true with q over two lines.

00:30:45.010 --> 00:30:45.590 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:30:45.590 --> 00:30:48.650 align:middle line:84%
Now in three dimensions
suppose I add up

00:30:48.650 --> 00:30:53.410 align:middle line:84%
less than q cubed lines,
maybe half of q cubed lines.

00:30:53.410 --> 00:30:53.950 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:30:53.950 --> 00:30:55.590 align:middle line:90%
Now this is a trickier wicket.

00:30:55.590 --> 00:30:58.010 align:middle line:90%
It depends which lines I pick.

00:30:58.010 --> 00:31:00.410 align:middle line:84%
If you were to pick
half of q cubed lines

00:31:00.410 --> 00:31:02.760 align:middle line:84%
randomly and add
them up, it would

00:31:02.760 --> 00:31:05.480 align:middle line:90%
be quite close to constant.

00:31:05.480 --> 00:31:07.760 align:middle line:84%
But if you pick
them cleverly, you

00:31:07.760 --> 00:31:10.060 align:middle line:84%
can make it not look
like a constant.

00:31:10.060 --> 00:31:11.220 align:middle line:90%
And here's how to do it.

00:31:11.220 --> 00:31:14.280 align:middle line:90%


00:31:14.280 --> 00:31:25.220 align:middle line:84%
So example of 1/2 q
cubed lines in Fq cubed.

00:31:25.220 --> 00:31:25.720 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:25.720 --> 00:31:27.400 align:middle line:90%
Here's what I'm going to do.

00:31:27.400 --> 00:31:41.280 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to pick 1/2 q
affine two planes Capital Pj.

00:31:41.280 --> 00:31:48.880 align:middle line:84%
And then in each
capital Pj, I pick

00:31:48.880 --> 00:31:55.050 align:middle line:84%
all the lines, which is
basically q squared lines.

00:31:55.050 --> 00:31:58.920 align:middle line:90%


00:31:58.920 --> 00:32:01.860 align:middle line:84%
So a two dimensional plane
has about q squared, q

00:32:01.860 --> 00:32:04.180 align:middle line:90%
squared plus q.

00:32:04.180 --> 00:32:06.700 align:middle line:84%
So you put this all
together, that's about half

00:32:06.700 --> 00:32:10.300 align:middle line:90%
of q cubed lines.

00:32:10.300 --> 00:32:14.740 align:middle line:84%
Now f, which is
the sum of L and L,

00:32:14.740 --> 00:32:20.580 align:middle line:84%
is supported on the
union of the Pj.

00:32:20.580 --> 00:32:26.580 align:middle line:84%
And the size of the Union of
the Pj is clearly at most half

00:32:26.580 --> 00:32:28.900 align:middle line:90%
of the space.

00:32:28.900 --> 00:32:33.820 align:middle line:84%
So the size of the union
of Pj is at most 1/2 q,

00:32:33.820 --> 00:32:38.380 align:middle line:84%
the number of j times q squared
number of points per plane 1/2 q

00:32:38.380 --> 00:32:39.300 align:middle line:90%
cubed.

00:32:39.300 --> 00:32:42.120 align:middle line:84%
So this thing is only supported
on about half of space.

00:32:42.120 --> 00:32:44.470 align:middle line:84%
There's no way that it's
approximately constant.

00:32:44.470 --> 00:32:47.980 align:middle line:90%


00:32:47.980 --> 00:32:50.900 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:32:50.900 --> 00:32:51.660 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:51.660 --> 00:32:56.380 align:middle line:84%
So in a certain sense, this
is the right threshold,

00:32:56.380 --> 00:32:58.490 align:middle line:84%
although you could also
imagine asking some more

00:32:58.490 --> 00:32:59.750 align:middle line:90%
refined questions.

00:32:59.750 --> 00:33:05.590 align:middle line:90%


00:33:05.590 --> 00:33:06.090 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:33:06.090 --> 00:33:11.530 align:middle line:90%


00:33:11.530 --> 00:33:12.110 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:33:12.110 --> 00:33:14.650 align:middle line:84%
I guess looking back
at the homework,

00:33:14.650 --> 00:33:17.690 align:middle line:84%
I mentioned a few things that
people tried that didn't work.

00:33:17.690 --> 00:33:20.050 align:middle line:84%
And I think the
most common thing

00:33:20.050 --> 00:33:23.090 align:middle line:84%
that people had a
tricky time finding

00:33:23.090 --> 00:33:28.330 align:middle line:84%
was that they should first group
the lines by their direction

00:33:28.330 --> 00:33:32.770 align:middle line:84%
and have these fw's, and
then group the fw's together

00:33:32.770 --> 00:33:34.930 align:middle line:90%
to make f.

00:33:34.930 --> 00:33:36.330 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:33:36.330 --> 00:33:40.170 align:middle line:84%
So I think I could have done
a better job giving direction

00:33:40.170 --> 00:33:43.210 align:middle line:84%
to look that way, look
in that direction.

00:33:43.210 --> 00:33:45.140 align:middle line:84%
But in hindsight, why
was that a good idea?

00:33:45.140 --> 00:33:48.570 align:middle line:90%


00:33:48.570 --> 00:33:51.950 align:middle line:84%
There's a saying that I like
about trying to learn stuff,

00:33:51.950 --> 00:33:54.770 align:middle line:84%
or trying to figure stuff out
that I learned from a Tai Chi

00:33:54.770 --> 00:33:55.890 align:middle line:90%
teacher.

00:33:55.890 --> 00:33:59.600 align:middle line:90%
They said, do what's easy first.

00:33:59.600 --> 00:34:02.928 align:middle line:84%
So if you are you trying
to, in math, for example,

00:34:02.928 --> 00:34:04.720 align:middle line:84%
add up a whole lot of
things and understand

00:34:04.720 --> 00:34:07.680 align:middle line:84%
what the sum is like, if there
are some pieces that you can add

00:34:07.680 --> 00:34:09.800 align:middle line:84%
up and you know
what those are like,

00:34:09.800 --> 00:34:13.520 align:middle line:84%
it's usually a good
idea to do that first.

00:34:13.520 --> 00:34:17.020 align:middle line:84%
And adding up parallel lines
is fairly easy to understand,

00:34:17.020 --> 00:34:19.699 align:middle line:90%
and so it won't always help.

00:34:19.699 --> 00:34:22.009 align:middle line:84%
But sometimes it's helpful
to do what's easy first.

00:34:22.009 --> 00:34:24.997 align:middle line:90%


00:34:24.997 --> 00:34:26.580 align:middle line:84%
Actually, same thing
happens in Fubini

00:34:26.580 --> 00:34:28.580 align:middle line:84%
when I teach analysis
at various levels.

00:34:28.580 --> 00:34:30.063 align:middle line:84%
When is it a good
idea to do Fubini

00:34:30.063 --> 00:34:31.480 align:middle line:84%
to switch the order
of integration

00:34:31.480 --> 00:34:33.159 align:middle line:84%
or switch the
order of summation?

00:34:33.159 --> 00:34:36.600 align:middle line:84%
You want to put the sum that
you do first to be the easy one.

00:34:36.600 --> 00:34:38.820 align:middle line:84%
That's almost always the
right way to organize it.

00:34:38.820 --> 00:34:44.639 align:middle line:90%


00:34:44.639 --> 00:34:45.139 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:45.139 --> 00:34:47.589 align:middle line:84%
So that was the recap
of the homework.

00:34:47.589 --> 00:34:50.600 align:middle line:90%


00:34:50.600 --> 00:34:53.000 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:55.510 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:34:55.510 --> 00:35:00.350 align:middle line:84%
Now we come to the main
topic of the day, which

00:35:00.350 --> 00:35:04.310 align:middle line:84%
is doing some projection
theory in Euclidean space

00:35:04.310 --> 00:35:06.470 align:middle line:84%
and thinking about
how projections

00:35:06.470 --> 00:35:08.490 align:middle line:90%
makes functions smoother.

00:35:08.490 --> 00:35:10.550 align:middle line:84%
So if you take a
function in R to the D

00:35:10.550 --> 00:35:14.670 align:middle line:84%
and you project it onto
something lower dimensional,

00:35:14.670 --> 00:35:17.930 align:middle line:84%
well, if you just pick one
lower dimensional projection,

00:35:17.930 --> 00:35:19.510 align:middle line:90%
it might not be very nice.

00:35:19.510 --> 00:35:22.290 align:middle line:84%
But if you look at all the
lower dimensional projections,

00:35:22.290 --> 00:35:24.550 align:middle line:90%
most of them will be smoother.

00:35:24.550 --> 00:35:26.850 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to
investigate that phenomenon.

00:35:26.850 --> 00:35:29.710 align:middle line:84%
And I hope you'll see that it's
very parallel to the large sieve

00:35:29.710 --> 00:35:31.570 align:middle line:90%
theory from number theory.

00:35:31.570 --> 00:36:02.370 align:middle line:90%


00:36:02.370 --> 00:36:03.110 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:36:03.110 --> 00:36:07.350 align:middle line:90%
Projections and smoothing.

00:36:07.350 --> 00:36:13.010 align:middle line:90%


00:36:13.010 --> 00:36:13.530 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:36:13.530 --> 00:36:15.730 align:middle line:90%
So here's our setup.

00:36:15.730 --> 00:36:19.930 align:middle line:84%
So f is now a function
on R to the D.

00:36:19.930 --> 00:36:21.780 align:middle line:90%
And v is going to be a subspace.

00:36:21.780 --> 00:36:25.450 align:middle line:90%


00:36:25.450 --> 00:36:29.810 align:middle line:84%
And recall, by the
projection of f, what I mean

00:36:29.810 --> 00:36:37.550 align:middle line:84%
is the integral over V perp f of
y plus z d volume v perp of ksi.

00:36:37.550 --> 00:36:42.090 align:middle line:90%


00:36:42.090 --> 00:36:47.810 align:middle line:84%
So this is a map from functions
on R to the D to functions on v.

00:36:47.810 --> 00:36:50.145 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:36:50.145 --> 00:36:52.873 align:middle line:90%
And I'm going to mostly focus--

00:36:52.873 --> 00:36:54.540 align:middle line:84%
everything works for
all the dimensions,

00:36:54.540 --> 00:36:56.375 align:middle line:84%
but for ease of
notation, whatever,

00:36:56.375 --> 00:36:58.000 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to mostly
focus on projecting

00:36:58.000 --> 00:36:59.960 align:middle line:90%
to one dimensional subspaces.

00:36:59.960 --> 00:37:03.880 align:middle line:84%
So if theta is a direction
in the circle pi theta

00:37:03.880 --> 00:37:06.760 align:middle line:90%
of f is going to mean pi--

00:37:06.760 --> 00:37:10.600 align:middle line:84%
abbreviation for pi
span of theta of f.

00:37:10.600 --> 00:37:11.400 align:middle line:90%
Direction.

00:37:11.400 --> 00:37:12.900 align:middle line:84%
Look at the line
in that direction.

00:37:12.900 --> 00:37:16.000 align:middle line:90%


00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:16.920 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:37:16.920 --> 00:37:19.000 align:middle line:84%
So here's a theorem
that says that if you

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:22.220 align:middle line:84%
start with a function, there's
very little regularity.

00:37:22.220 --> 00:37:24.760 align:middle line:84%
Most of the projections
are even smooth.

00:37:24.760 --> 00:37:31.120 align:middle line:84%
So theorem says if f is an
L2 function on R to the D,

00:37:31.120 --> 00:37:35.520 align:middle line:84%
and the support of f
is in the unit ball,

00:37:35.520 --> 00:37:41.120 align:middle line:84%
then if I integrate
over this sphere

00:37:41.120 --> 00:37:46.680 align:middle line:84%
and I take the projection
onto the line in the theta

00:37:46.680 --> 00:37:53.510 align:middle line:84%
direction of f and I take
it CK norm, then that

00:37:53.510 --> 00:37:58.470 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by the L2 norm of f,
provided that the dimension is

00:37:58.470 --> 00:37:59.870 align:middle line:90%
big enough.

00:37:59.870 --> 00:38:03.270 align:middle line:84%
So I add the hypothesis
at the dimension,

00:38:03.270 --> 00:38:08.670 align:middle line:84%
which would be dimension D minus
1 over 2 should be bigger than

00:38:08.670 --> 00:38:10.170 align:middle line:90%
1/2 plus k.

00:38:10.170 --> 00:38:12.870 align:middle line:90%


00:38:12.870 --> 00:38:14.610 align:middle line:84%
You can unwind
that a little bit.

00:38:14.610 --> 00:38:18.230 align:middle line:84%
It says D is bigger
than something.

00:38:18.230 --> 00:38:23.550 align:middle line:90%
So for example, D is 7.

00:38:23.550 --> 00:38:25.670 align:middle line:90%
Then you can take k equals 2.

00:38:25.670 --> 00:38:29.550 align:middle line:84%
So in seven dimensions you
take just an L2 function.

00:38:29.550 --> 00:38:31.470 align:middle line:84%
If you project it
down to one dimension

00:38:31.470 --> 00:38:34.500 align:middle line:84%
in a typical direction, you'll
get something that's C2.

00:38:34.500 --> 00:38:38.990 align:middle line:90%


00:38:38.990 --> 00:38:40.270 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:40.270 --> 00:38:43.150 align:middle line:84%
I'm actually not sure to whom
to attribute this theorem.

00:38:43.150 --> 00:38:45.950 align:middle line:84%
I'm in the process of doing
some historical research

00:38:45.950 --> 00:38:49.450 align:middle line:90%
and maybe I'll know next class.

00:38:49.450 --> 00:38:50.110 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:38:50.110 --> 00:38:53.370 align:middle line:90%


00:38:53.370 --> 00:38:56.570 align:middle line:84%
So this theorem is also based
on the Fourier transform

00:38:56.570 --> 00:38:58.410 align:middle line:84%
and the way the Fourier
transform interacts

00:38:58.410 --> 00:39:00.770 align:middle line:90%
with projections.

00:39:00.770 --> 00:39:02.680 align:middle line:84%
So now let's think
about how that works.

00:39:02.680 --> 00:39:21.570 align:middle line:90%


00:39:21.570 --> 00:39:25.150 align:middle line:84%
Fourier transform
and projections.

00:39:25.150 --> 00:39:33.530 align:middle line:90%


00:39:33.530 --> 00:39:34.450 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:39:34.450 --> 00:39:38.070 align:middle line:84%
So f is a function on R to the
D. It has a Fourier transform.

00:39:38.070 --> 00:39:40.530 align:middle line:84%
We've talked about
it pi v of f is

00:39:40.530 --> 00:39:44.510 align:middle line:84%
a function on v. It also
has a Fourier transform.

00:39:44.510 --> 00:39:45.980 align:middle line:90%
I just remind you how it works.

00:39:45.980 --> 00:39:48.760 align:middle line:90%
So v is a vector space.

00:39:48.760 --> 00:39:53.600 align:middle line:84%
It basically works the same
way as on Euclidean space.

00:39:53.600 --> 00:39:54.280 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:39:54.280 --> 00:39:59.680 align:middle line:84%
So suppose I have a
function g from V to C.

00:39:59.680 --> 00:40:03.560 align:middle line:84%
Then g hat will also be
a function from V to C.

00:40:03.560 --> 00:40:11.200 align:middle line:84%
And g hat of ksi will be the
integral over v of g of y, e

00:40:11.200 --> 00:40:15.400 align:middle line:90%
to the minus 2 pi iy dot ksi dy.

00:40:15.400 --> 00:40:19.360 align:middle line:84%
But dy means with the volume
form for my vector space V.

00:40:19.360 --> 00:40:23.260 align:middle line:90%
So that's the Fourier transform.

00:40:23.260 --> 00:40:23.760 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:40:23.760 --> 00:40:27.240 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: What do you add
the 2 pi key factor here?

00:40:27.240 --> 00:40:31.160 align:middle line:84%
That's normally not include
a general Fourier transform.

00:40:31.160 --> 00:40:32.327 align:middle line:90%
Is that just a convention?

00:40:32.327 --> 00:40:33.160 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:40:33.160 --> 00:40:35.302 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, why
is there a 2 pi here?

00:40:35.302 --> 00:40:37.760 align:middle line:84%
There are a couple of different
conventions for the Fourier

00:40:37.760 --> 00:40:38.720 align:middle line:90%
transform.

00:40:38.720 --> 00:40:41.120 align:middle line:90%
One of them has a 2 pi here.

00:40:41.120 --> 00:40:44.870 align:middle line:84%
The other one has a 1 over
2 pi to the D in the front.

00:40:44.870 --> 00:40:47.103 align:middle line:84%
Those are, as far as I
can tell, equally good.

00:40:47.103 --> 00:40:49.270 align:middle line:84%
And they both involve some
slightly annoying factors

00:40:49.270 --> 00:40:50.170 align:middle line:90%
of 2 pi.

00:40:50.170 --> 00:40:51.670 align:middle line:84%
There's another
convention where you

00:40:51.670 --> 00:40:53.380 align:middle line:90%
write neither of those things.

00:40:53.380 --> 00:40:57.350 align:middle line:84%
That, strictly speaking, is not
correct, but it's convenient

00:40:57.350 --> 00:40:58.670 align:middle line:90%
and it usually is OK.

00:40:58.670 --> 00:41:02.270 align:middle line:90%


00:41:02.270 --> 00:41:05.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:05.190 --> 00:41:09.670 align:middle line:84%
Now we can do Fourier inversion
where we recover g of y.

00:41:09.670 --> 00:41:10.690 align:middle line:90%
Do Fourier inversion.

00:41:10.690 --> 00:41:17.190 align:middle line:84%
That's the integral over V g hat
of ksi to the 2 pi iy dot ksi

00:41:17.190 --> 00:41:19.170 align:middle line:90%
d volume V of ksi.

00:41:19.170 --> 00:41:22.910 align:middle line:90%


00:41:22.910 --> 00:41:23.410 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:23.410 --> 00:41:25.780 align:middle line:84%
So that's how the Fourier
transform works on a subspace.

00:41:25.780 --> 00:41:29.710 align:middle line:90%


00:41:29.710 --> 00:41:33.090 align:middle line:84%
And now, what does projection
do to the Fourier transform?

00:41:33.090 --> 00:41:36.270 align:middle line:84%
There is an elegant
formula lemma.

00:41:36.270 --> 00:41:38.390 align:middle line:90%
Call it a dictionary lemma.

00:41:38.390 --> 00:41:43.420 align:middle line:84%
Translates between
the projection

00:41:43.420 --> 00:41:46.460 align:middle line:84%
on the physical side and
projection on the Fourier side.

00:41:46.460 --> 00:41:49.180 align:middle line:84%
It's analogous to something that
I called the dictionary lemma

00:41:49.180 --> 00:41:51.340 align:middle line:90%
when we were doing large sieve.

00:41:51.340 --> 00:41:51.840 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:41:51.840 --> 00:41:53.980 align:middle line:90%
It says the following thing.

00:41:53.980 --> 00:41:58.100 align:middle line:84%
If I have a function
on R to the D,

00:41:58.100 --> 00:42:02.180 align:middle line:84%
then if I project it to V and
take its Fourier transform,

00:42:02.180 --> 00:42:10.740 align:middle line:84%
it's just f hat of
ksi for all ksi in V.

00:42:10.740 --> 00:42:11.240 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:42:11.240 --> 00:42:12.440 align:middle line:90%
So let's process a second.

00:42:12.440 --> 00:42:15.020 align:middle line:84%
So this is a function on v.
Its Fourier transform is only

00:42:15.020 --> 00:42:18.140 align:middle line:84%
defined on V. So this
left-hand side only makes sense

00:42:18.140 --> 00:42:21.700 align:middle line:84%
if ksi is in V. But it's
equal to f hat of ksi,

00:42:21.700 --> 00:42:27.100 align:middle line:84%
and f hat makes sense for
ksi anywhere in R to the D.

00:42:27.100 --> 00:42:28.070 align:middle line:90%
So here's the proof.

00:42:28.070 --> 00:42:31.460 align:middle line:90%


00:42:31.460 --> 00:42:33.940 align:middle line:84%
Let's just expand out
what everything means.

00:42:33.940 --> 00:42:40.120 align:middle line:84%
So the left-hand side is the
integral over V pi vf of y, e

00:42:40.120 --> 00:42:49.000 align:middle line:84%
to the minus 2 pi i ksi
dot y d volume v of y.

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:51.280 align:middle line:90%
But what is the projection?

00:42:51.280 --> 00:42:52.500 align:middle line:90%
Pi vf of y.

00:42:52.500 --> 00:42:56.360 align:middle line:84%
That's also an integral, and
it's an integral over V perp.

00:42:56.360 --> 00:43:00.760 align:middle line:84%
So that's the integral over
V, integral over V perp,

00:43:00.760 --> 00:43:06.960 align:middle line:84%
f of y plus z, d
volume v perp of z.

00:43:06.960 --> 00:43:11.240 align:middle line:84%
So that was this
thing, e to the minus 2

00:43:11.240 --> 00:43:15.540 align:middle line:90%
pi iy dot ksi, d volume v of y.

00:43:15.540 --> 00:43:18.560 align:middle line:90%


00:43:18.560 --> 00:43:19.300 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:43:19.300 --> 00:43:23.240 align:middle line:84%
So now notice that altogether,
if you put this stuff together

00:43:23.240 --> 00:43:29.160 align:middle line:84%
and that and that together, we
are integrating over R to the D.

00:43:29.160 --> 00:43:32.880 align:middle line:84%
And so more precisely, we can do
of a change of variables here.

00:43:32.880 --> 00:43:41.456 align:middle line:84%
We can say x is y plus z
and dx is d volume v of y,

00:43:41.456 --> 00:43:45.870 align:middle line:90%
d volume v perp of z.

00:43:45.870 --> 00:43:47.390 align:middle line:90%
So this is f of x.

00:43:47.390 --> 00:43:50.230 align:middle line:90%
This stuff is just dx.

00:43:50.230 --> 00:43:52.390 align:middle line:90%
Now who is this?

00:43:52.390 --> 00:44:05.070 align:middle line:84%
Well, because z is in V perp
and ksi is in V, z dot ksi is 0.

00:44:05.070 --> 00:44:10.910 align:middle line:84%
So e to the minus 2 pi iy dot
ksi is the same thing as e

00:44:10.910 --> 00:44:16.750 align:middle line:84%
to the minus 2 pi
i y plus z dot ksi.

00:44:16.750 --> 00:44:20.390 align:middle line:84%
Changed it by z dot
ksi, which was 0, which

00:44:20.390 --> 00:44:22.550 align:middle line:90%
is e to the minus 2 pi ix.

00:44:22.550 --> 00:44:26.230 align:middle line:90%


00:44:26.230 --> 00:44:28.150 align:middle line:84%
So I can rewrite
everything in terms

00:44:28.150 --> 00:44:36.100 align:middle line:84%
of x and it's just my integral
f of x, e to the minus 2 pi

00:44:36.100 --> 00:44:38.080 align:middle line:90%
x dot ksi dx.

00:44:38.080 --> 00:44:42.700 align:middle line:90%


00:44:42.700 --> 00:44:43.200 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:44:43.200 --> 00:44:46.560 align:middle line:84%
So that's f hat x ksi, and
that's what we wanted to prove.

00:44:46.560 --> 00:44:53.180 align:middle line:90%


00:44:53.180 --> 00:44:54.160 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:44:54.160 --> 00:44:54.660 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:44:54.660 --> 00:45:08.870 align:middle line:90%


00:45:08.870 --> 00:45:09.370 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:09.370 --> 00:45:28.180 align:middle line:90%


00:45:28.180 --> 00:45:29.900 align:middle line:90%
So let's see.

00:45:29.900 --> 00:45:31.120 align:middle line:90%
How might we use this?

00:45:31.120 --> 00:45:32.320 align:middle line:90%
What might this tell us?

00:45:32.320 --> 00:45:35.730 align:middle line:90%


00:45:35.730 --> 00:45:39.450 align:middle line:84%
So we're interested in
this projection thing.

00:45:39.450 --> 00:45:41.370 align:middle line:84%
And the projection
plays very nicely

00:45:41.370 --> 00:45:43.370 align:middle line:90%
with the Fourier transform.

00:45:43.370 --> 00:45:46.210 align:middle line:84%
And so anything else that
plays nicely with the Fourier

00:45:46.210 --> 00:45:47.970 align:middle line:84%
transform, we could
try to figure out how

00:45:47.970 --> 00:45:50.290 align:middle line:90%
it interacts with projection.

00:45:50.290 --> 00:45:53.170 align:middle line:84%
And one of the fundamental
things that interacts nicely

00:45:53.170 --> 00:45:54.990 align:middle line:84%
with the Fourier
transform is the L2 norm,

00:45:54.990 --> 00:45:56.490 align:middle line:90%
because we have Plancherel.

00:45:56.490 --> 00:46:00.210 align:middle line:84%
So we can write f L2
in terms of f hat.

00:46:00.210 --> 00:46:04.170 align:middle line:84%
And f hat is closely
related to pi v of f hat.

00:46:04.170 --> 00:46:05.810 align:middle line:90%
Let's just see what happens.

00:46:05.810 --> 00:46:06.950 align:middle line:90%
What does that tell us?

00:46:06.950 --> 00:46:11.810 align:middle line:90%


00:46:11.810 --> 00:46:23.530 align:middle line:84%
So I'll call this
relating f L2 and pi v

00:46:23.530 --> 00:46:26.910 align:middle line:90%
of f via the Fourier transform.

00:46:26.910 --> 00:46:31.290 align:middle line:90%


00:46:31.290 --> 00:46:33.710 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to focus on
pi theta of f, because that

00:46:33.710 --> 00:46:35.060 align:middle line:90%
will make this the easiest.

00:46:35.060 --> 00:46:38.990 align:middle line:90%


00:46:38.990 --> 00:46:39.730 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:46:39.730 --> 00:46:46.470 align:middle line:84%
So f L2 squared is
f hat L2 squared.

00:46:46.470 --> 00:46:47.590 align:middle line:90%
Write that out.

00:46:47.590 --> 00:46:55.950 align:middle line:84%
It's the integral over R to the
D f hat of ksi squared d ksi.

00:46:55.950 --> 00:46:57.090 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:46:57.090 --> 00:47:03.030 align:middle line:84%
And the different-- if I
take pi theta of f hat,

00:47:03.030 --> 00:47:05.710 align:middle line:84%
that will correspond to
f hat on different lines

00:47:05.710 --> 00:47:08.070 align:middle line:90%
through the origin.

00:47:08.070 --> 00:47:11.670 align:middle line:84%
So that suggests-- let's
separate this out in different

00:47:11.670 --> 00:47:15.750 align:middle line:84%
directions by writing
it in polar coordinates.

00:47:15.750 --> 00:47:19.830 align:middle line:84%
So this is equal to the integral
over the d minus 1 sphere

00:47:19.830 --> 00:47:27.710 align:middle line:84%
integral from 0 to infinity,
f hat of r theta squared

00:47:27.710 --> 00:47:30.890 align:middle line:90%
r to the d minus 1, dr d theta.

00:47:30.890 --> 00:47:37.620 align:middle line:90%


00:47:37.620 --> 00:47:38.120 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:38.120 --> 00:47:48.220 align:middle line:84%
And let me do this little trick
to also include negative r,

00:47:48.220 --> 00:47:51.100 align:middle line:84%
so that once I fix theta I
have a nice integral from

00:47:51.100 --> 00:47:54.340 align:middle line:90%
minus infinity to infinity.

00:47:54.340 --> 00:47:55.780 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:47:55.780 --> 00:48:02.130 align:middle line:84%
So this guy is related to
pi theta of f by this lemma.

00:48:02.130 --> 00:48:07.300 align:middle line:90%


00:48:07.300 --> 00:48:14.000 align:middle line:84%
So this is 1/2 integral
over Sd minus 1 d theta.

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:16.440 align:middle line:84%
So I'm averaging over all
the different directions.

00:48:16.440 --> 00:48:18.380 align:middle line:90%
And what am I averaging?

00:48:18.380 --> 00:48:21.780 align:middle line:84%
Integrating from minus
infinity to infinity,

00:48:21.780 --> 00:48:27.860 align:middle line:90%
pi theta f hat of r theta.

00:48:27.860 --> 00:48:36.850 align:middle line:90%
r to the d minus 1 dr.

00:48:36.850 --> 00:48:39.470 align:middle line:90%
What is this thing inside here?

00:48:39.470 --> 00:48:41.130 align:middle line:84%
At first you might
have thought you

00:48:41.130 --> 00:48:44.580 align:middle line:84%
might get the L2 norm of
pi theta of f squared.

00:48:44.580 --> 00:48:47.170 align:middle line:90%


00:48:47.170 --> 00:48:51.610 align:middle line:84%
So that would be the L2 norm
of pi theta of f squared.

00:48:51.610 --> 00:48:56.690 align:middle line:84%
This has this extra
factor here which

00:48:56.690 --> 00:48:59.130 align:middle line:84%
heavily weights
large frequencies

00:48:59.130 --> 00:49:02.410 align:middle line:84%
and gives a very low weight
to small frequencies.

00:49:02.410 --> 00:49:03.010 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:49:03.010 --> 00:49:04.543 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: That's Sobolev norm.

00:49:04.543 --> 00:49:05.710 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: That's right.

00:49:05.710 --> 00:49:08.010 align:middle line:90%
This thing is a Sobolev norm.

00:49:08.010 --> 00:49:11.530 align:middle line:84%
So What naturally appears
here is Sobolev norm.

00:49:11.530 --> 00:49:13.890 align:middle line:84%
And now let's pause
and we'll review

00:49:13.890 --> 00:49:17.070 align:middle line:84%
Sobolev norms and some
important facts about them.

00:49:17.070 --> 00:49:23.570 align:middle line:90%


00:49:23.570 --> 00:49:24.390 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:49:24.390 --> 00:49:42.200 align:middle line:90%


00:49:42.200 --> 00:49:43.186 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:43.186 --> 00:49:46.720 align:middle line:90%
So definition.

00:49:46.720 --> 00:49:52.440 align:middle line:84%
If I have a function
g on a vector space,

00:49:52.440 --> 00:49:53.840 align:middle line:90%
like a subspace of--

00:49:53.840 --> 00:49:56.160 align:middle line:90%
a space with the Euclidean norm.

00:49:56.160 --> 00:49:57.680 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:49:57.680 --> 00:49:59.640 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: This is about
the dictionary lemma.

00:49:59.640 --> 00:50:02.980 align:middle line:84%
I'm wondering what class of
functions that applies to.

00:50:02.980 --> 00:50:08.000 align:middle line:84%
Because if f is an L2 function
so f hat is L2 function,

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:13.687 align:middle line:84%
how is its value on a measure
0 subset being meaningful?

00:50:13.687 --> 00:50:14.520 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

00:50:14.520 --> 00:50:15.500 align:middle line:90%
OK, great.

00:50:15.500 --> 00:50:18.480 align:middle line:84%
So the going back to
the dictionary lemma.

00:50:18.480 --> 00:50:21.720 align:middle line:84%
The question was, for
which class of functions

00:50:21.720 --> 00:50:23.765 align:middle line:90%
does this actually make sense?

00:50:23.765 --> 00:50:25.640 align:middle line:84%
And if you look at what
I wrote on the board,

00:50:25.640 --> 00:50:27.020 align:middle line:90%
it's a little suspicious.

00:50:27.020 --> 00:50:30.137 align:middle line:84%
It just says that
f is a function.

00:50:30.137 --> 00:50:31.720 align:middle line:84%
And if f is just a
function, actually,

00:50:31.720 --> 00:50:36.580 align:middle line:84%
none of the sides of this
equation in general makes sense.

00:50:36.580 --> 00:50:39.180 align:middle line:84%
One thing that would
be clearly sufficient

00:50:39.180 --> 00:50:43.220 align:middle line:90%
is if f was a Schwarz function.

00:50:43.220 --> 00:50:46.338 align:middle line:84%
If f is a Schwarz function,
f hat is a Schwarz function,

00:50:46.338 --> 00:50:47.880 align:middle line:84%
the projection is
a Schwarz function,

00:50:47.880 --> 00:50:49.005 align:middle line:90%
this is a Schwarz function.

00:50:49.005 --> 00:50:51.100 align:middle line:90%
So that's all OK.

00:50:51.100 --> 00:50:54.460 align:middle line:84%
If f is just L2, it's
not immediately obvious

00:50:54.460 --> 00:50:58.140 align:middle line:84%
how all of these things
would be defined.

00:50:58.140 --> 00:51:01.520 align:middle line:84%
So let's think about
this way for now.

00:51:01.520 --> 00:51:05.900 align:middle line:90%


00:51:05.900 --> 00:51:07.820 align:middle line:84%
It's fairly often
the case that we

00:51:07.820 --> 00:51:10.340 align:middle line:84%
can prove things about
general L2 functions

00:51:10.340 --> 00:51:12.640 align:middle line:84%
by first proving them
for Schwarz functions,

00:51:12.640 --> 00:51:15.232 align:middle line:90%
and then proving--

00:51:15.232 --> 00:51:17.690 align:middle line:84%
then using the fact that Schwarz
functions are dense in L2.

00:51:17.690 --> 00:51:21.190 align:middle line:90%


00:51:21.190 --> 00:51:21.690 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:21.690 --> 00:51:28.670 align:middle line:90%


00:51:28.670 --> 00:51:29.170 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:29.170 --> 00:51:30.496 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:51:30.496 --> 00:51:33.990 align:middle line:84%
OK, so we were remembering
what is a Sobolev norm.

00:51:33.990 --> 00:51:40.810 align:middle line:84%
So if I have a function
on v, then g HS

00:51:40.810 --> 00:51:46.090 align:middle line:84%
dot squared is the
integral over v.

00:51:46.090 --> 00:51:50.490 align:middle line:84%
I'll take the norm of
g hat of ksi squared.

00:51:50.490 --> 00:51:54.500 align:middle line:84%
And then I'll put here
the norm of ksi to the 2S.

00:51:54.500 --> 00:51:58.450 align:middle line:90%


00:51:58.450 --> 00:52:03.050 align:middle line:84%
This makes sense for
any real number S,

00:52:03.050 --> 00:52:09.550 align:middle line:84%
and it has something to do
with the smoothness of g.

00:52:09.550 --> 00:52:11.667 align:middle line:84%
And in particular, if
S is a natural number,

00:52:11.667 --> 00:52:13.250 align:middle line:84%
then it has an
interpretation in terms

00:52:13.250 --> 00:52:15.770 align:middle line:90%
of L2 norms of derivatives.

00:52:15.770 --> 00:52:25.120 align:middle line:84%
So g H1 dot squared is the sum
over different directions j

00:52:25.120 --> 00:52:30.560 align:middle line:84%
of the j-th derivative of g L2
squared, at least approximately,

00:52:30.560 --> 00:52:36.760 align:middle line:84%
maybe exactly, and then
higher values of S--

00:52:36.760 --> 00:52:40.360 align:middle line:84%
higher values of S correspond
to taking more derivatives.

00:52:40.360 --> 00:52:41.880 align:middle line:84%
So I'll just put
one more and you'll

00:52:41.880 --> 00:52:48.600 align:middle line:84%
see the pattern H2 dot squared
is around the sum over j1 and j2

00:52:48.600 --> 00:52:53.280 align:middle line:84%
of the second derivative in
the j1 j2 directions of g,

00:52:53.280 --> 00:52:56.680 align:middle line:90%
L2 squared, and so on.

00:52:56.680 --> 00:52:58.384 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:58.384 --> 00:53:03.400 align:middle line:84%
And if S is not an
integer, then there's

00:53:03.400 --> 00:53:05.940 align:middle line:84%
not a direct interpretation
of this form,

00:53:05.940 --> 00:53:07.920 align:middle line:84%
but it is still
kind of measuring

00:53:07.920 --> 00:53:11.800 align:middle line:90%
how smooth the function g is.

00:53:11.800 --> 00:53:13.980 align:middle line:90%
There is also a regular.

00:53:13.980 --> 00:53:16.280 align:middle line:84%
So this is the Sobolev
norm with a dot.

00:53:16.280 --> 00:53:19.430 align:middle line:84%
It's called the
homogeneous Sobolev norm.

00:53:19.430 --> 00:53:22.530 align:middle line:84%
There's a version without the
dot, which is defined like this.

00:53:22.530 --> 00:53:26.150 align:middle line:90%


00:53:26.150 --> 00:53:34.710 align:middle line:84%
g HS squared is the integral
over v g hat of ksi squared 1

00:53:34.710 --> 00:53:38.440 align:middle line:84%
plus the norm of ksi
squared to the S d

00:53:38.440 --> 00:53:44.550 align:middle line:84%
ksi, which is roughly the same
as if you took out the biggest

00:53:44.550 --> 00:53:45.050 align:middle line:90%
power.

00:53:45.050 --> 00:53:51.030 align:middle line:84%
So it'd be 1 plus ksi to the
2s, and the one contributes g L2

00:53:51.030 --> 00:53:55.090 align:middle line:84%
squared, and the ksi to
the 2S is this thing.

00:53:55.090 --> 00:53:58.620 align:middle line:84%
So it contributes
HS dot squared.

00:53:58.620 --> 00:54:05.690 align:middle line:90%


00:54:05.690 --> 00:54:06.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:54:06.190 --> 00:54:11.990 align:middle line:90%


00:54:11.990 --> 00:54:12.790 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:54:12.790 --> 00:54:16.630 align:middle line:84%
So there's a well-known set
of theorems called the Sobolev

00:54:16.630 --> 00:54:21.210 align:middle line:84%
embedding theorems, which
imply that if g is in a Sobolev

00:54:21.210 --> 00:54:24.330 align:middle line:84%
space for a big enough
S, then it is continuous,

00:54:24.330 --> 00:54:28.730 align:middle line:84%
and if even bigger S,
then it's C1, and so on.

00:54:28.730 --> 00:54:31.760 align:middle line:90%
So I will write a summary.

00:54:31.760 --> 00:54:39.010 align:middle line:90%


00:54:39.010 --> 00:54:41.890 align:middle line:90%
Sobolev embedding.

00:54:41.890 --> 00:54:48.490 align:middle line:84%
If S is bigger than
1/2 the dimension of V,

00:54:48.490 --> 00:54:54.495 align:middle line:84%
then g L infinity is
bounded by g in HS.

00:54:54.495 --> 00:54:57.690 align:middle line:90%


00:54:57.690 --> 00:55:00.510 align:middle line:84%
And if g is in HS,
then g is continuous.

00:55:00.510 --> 00:55:05.890 align:middle line:90%


00:55:05.890 --> 00:55:11.770 align:middle line:84%
If S is bigger than some k
plus 1/2 the dimension of V,

00:55:11.770 --> 00:55:18.620 align:middle line:84%
then the k-th derivatives of
g are bounded by the HS norm.

00:55:18.620 --> 00:55:21.840 align:middle line:90%


00:55:21.840 --> 00:55:23.810 align:middle line:90%
And if g is in HS, then its CK.

00:55:23.810 --> 00:55:37.912 align:middle line:90%


00:55:37.912 --> 00:55:38.412 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:55:38.412 --> 00:55:42.348 align:middle line:90%


00:55:42.348 --> 00:55:44.810 align:middle line:84%
Any questions or comments
about Sobolev spaces?

00:55:44.810 --> 00:55:57.320 align:middle line:90%


00:55:57.320 --> 00:55:59.120 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:55:59.120 --> 00:56:07.320 align:middle line:84%
So now that we have recalled
that, if we look back here,

00:56:07.320 --> 00:56:11.320 align:middle line:84%
we will recognize what
appears here as a Sobolev

00:56:11.320 --> 00:56:13.950 align:middle line:90%
norm of the projection.

00:56:13.950 --> 00:56:17.630 align:middle line:84%
So the L2 norm square root
of f is this integral.

00:56:17.630 --> 00:56:24.430 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here is the
HS norm of pi theta of f.

00:56:24.430 --> 00:56:33.820 align:middle line:84%
So this is 1/2 integral over the
d minus 1 sphere pi theta of f H

00:56:33.820 --> 00:56:40.670 align:middle line:84%
d minus 1 over 2
dot squared d theta.

00:56:40.670 --> 00:56:41.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:56:41.190 --> 00:56:43.550 align:middle line:84%
Where did this come from,
and why does it have a dot?

00:56:43.550 --> 00:56:47.630 align:middle line:84%
This r is the norm
of my frequency ksi.

00:56:47.630 --> 00:56:52.230 align:middle line:84%
So this is the norm
of ksi to the 2S.

00:56:52.230 --> 00:56:55.110 align:middle line:90%
So S is d minus 1 over 2.

00:56:55.110 --> 00:56:56.210 align:middle line:90%
And it's homogeneous.

00:56:56.210 --> 00:56:57.570 align:middle line:90%
We don't have this extra one.

00:56:57.570 --> 00:56:58.490 align:middle line:90%
So there's a dot.

00:56:58.490 --> 00:57:03.750 align:middle line:90%


00:57:03.750 --> 00:57:04.510 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:57:04.510 --> 00:57:05.010 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:57:05.010 --> 00:57:10.770 align:middle line:90%


00:57:10.770 --> 00:57:11.270 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:57:11.270 --> 00:57:19.020 align:middle line:90%


00:57:19.020 --> 00:57:19.940 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:57:19.940 --> 00:57:24.020 align:middle line:84%
So now you can probably
have a good guess

00:57:24.020 --> 00:57:27.460 align:middle line:84%
of how we would like
to prove this theorem.

00:57:27.460 --> 00:57:33.260 align:middle line:84%
The L2 norm controls an integral
like this with the Sobolev norm.

00:57:33.260 --> 00:57:35.500 align:middle line:84%
The Sobolev embedding tells
us that the Sobolev norm

00:57:35.500 --> 00:57:38.020 align:middle line:90%
controls the CK norm.

00:57:38.020 --> 00:57:39.020 align:middle line:90%
So that's the plan.

00:57:39.020 --> 00:57:39.740 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:57:39.740 --> 00:57:43.360 align:middle line:84%
But technically, there is
a small technical issue,

00:57:43.360 --> 00:57:45.820 align:middle line:84%
which has to do with
the dot or the no dot.

00:57:45.820 --> 00:57:48.220 align:middle line:84%
Dot and no dot,
homogeneous, not homogeneous

00:57:48.220 --> 00:57:50.380 align:middle line:90%
are both natural and important.

00:57:50.380 --> 00:57:52.800 align:middle line:84%
Homogeneous one will occur
naturally in some places.

00:57:52.800 --> 00:57:54.900 align:middle line:90%
It naturally occurred here.

00:57:54.900 --> 00:57:56.740 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand,
Sobolev embedding

00:57:56.740 --> 00:58:03.480 align:middle line:84%
is a theorem that requires the
non-homogeneous Sobolev space.

00:58:03.480 --> 00:58:05.850 align:middle line:84%
So we need to do a little
bit of work to get between.

00:58:05.850 --> 00:58:34.520 align:middle line:90%


00:58:34.520 --> 00:58:36.760 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:36.760 --> 00:58:38.450 align:middle line:84%
So now we can do the
proof of theorem.

00:58:38.450 --> 00:58:44.440 align:middle line:90%


00:58:44.440 --> 00:58:45.840 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:58:45.840 --> 00:58:53.200 align:middle line:84%
So integral SD minus
1 pi theta f CK d

00:58:53.200 --> 00:59:03.360 align:middle line:84%
theta is bounded by integral SD
minus 1 pi theta f H d minus 1

00:59:03.360 --> 00:59:07.760 align:middle line:84%
over 2 without the
dot squared d theta.

00:59:07.760 --> 00:59:09.570 align:middle line:90%
So this is Sobolev embedding.

00:59:09.570 --> 00:59:12.510 align:middle line:90%


00:59:12.510 --> 00:59:14.990 align:middle line:84%
And the hypothesis
about d up there

00:59:14.990 --> 00:59:17.110 align:middle line:84%
is just exactly the
hypothesis that you

00:59:17.110 --> 00:59:21.370 align:middle line:84%
need for this to be true when
you plug in Sobolev embedding.

00:59:21.370 --> 00:59:24.190 align:middle line:90%


00:59:24.190 --> 00:59:25.050 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:59:25.050 --> 00:59:28.150 align:middle line:84%
Now let's open up the
definition of this thing.

00:59:28.150 --> 00:59:31.850 align:middle line:84%
And we'll almost see
the f L2 norm squared.

00:59:31.850 --> 00:59:34.110 align:middle line:90%
But not quite.

00:59:34.110 --> 00:59:37.910 align:middle line:84%
So this is around
integral of SD minus 1,

00:59:37.910 --> 00:59:42.550 align:middle line:84%
integral from minus
infinity to infinity, f hat

00:59:42.550 --> 00:59:44.630 align:middle line:90%
of r theta squared.

00:59:44.630 --> 00:59:50.280 align:middle line:84%
And we'll have 1 plus r to
the d minus 1 dr d theta.

00:59:50.280 --> 00:59:54.230 align:middle line:90%


00:59:54.230 --> 00:59:56.430 align:middle line:84%
So we don't have a
dot that requires

00:59:56.430 --> 01:00:01.030 align:middle line:84%
us to put this extra one
that we didn't have before.

01:00:01.030 --> 01:00:01.770 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:00:01.770 --> 01:00:03.830 align:middle line:90%
So you have a sum of two pieces.

01:00:03.830 --> 01:00:05.870 align:middle line:84%
In real analysis, we
usually think about which

01:00:05.870 --> 01:00:08.300 align:middle line:90%
of the two pieces is bigger.

01:00:08.300 --> 01:00:11.540 align:middle line:84%
So if r is bigger than
1, this piece dominates.

01:00:11.540 --> 01:00:16.500 align:middle line:84%
And if r is smaller than
1, that piece dominates.

01:00:16.500 --> 01:00:22.220 align:middle line:84%
So the integral SD
minus 1 integral r

01:00:22.220 --> 01:00:28.560 align:middle line:84%
bigger than 1 f hat of r theta
squared r to the d minus 1 dr

01:00:28.560 --> 01:00:30.300 align:middle line:90%
d theta.

01:00:30.300 --> 01:00:33.820 align:middle line:84%
That's called that
term number one.

01:00:33.820 --> 01:00:39.780 align:middle line:84%
Plus the integral SD minus
1 integral r smaller than 1

01:00:39.780 --> 01:00:49.180 align:middle line:84%
f hat of r theta squared
1 times 1 dr d theta.

01:00:49.180 --> 01:00:50.520 align:middle line:90%
Let's call this piece two.

01:00:50.520 --> 01:00:56.100 align:middle line:90%


01:00:56.100 --> 01:00:58.530 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:00:58.530 --> 01:01:04.340 align:middle line:84%
So piece one is clearly smaller
than what we had before,

01:01:04.340 --> 01:01:07.160 align:middle line:90%
which was f L2 squared.

01:01:07.160 --> 01:01:10.830 align:middle line:84%
So piece is 1 smaller
than f L2 squared.

01:01:10.830 --> 01:01:15.840 align:middle line:90%


01:01:15.840 --> 01:01:18.840 align:middle line:90%
Piece two.

01:01:18.840 --> 01:01:19.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:01:19.640 --> 01:01:22.560 align:middle line:84%
In piece two, I think it's
no longer really helpful

01:01:22.560 --> 01:01:25.880 align:middle line:84%
to think of this as being
related to polar coordinates.

01:01:25.880 --> 01:01:29.760 align:middle line:84%
We're integrating over a
sphere across an interval,

01:01:29.760 --> 01:01:32.920 align:middle line:90%
and that's a finite volume.

01:01:32.920 --> 01:01:34.760 align:middle line:84%
And so what I'd
like to put here is

01:01:34.760 --> 01:01:37.040 align:middle line:84%
just that it's bounded
by a constant, which

01:01:37.040 --> 01:01:39.950 align:middle line:84%
is the volume times the
biggest possible size of this.

01:01:39.950 --> 01:01:50.040 align:middle line:90%


01:01:50.040 --> 01:01:50.720 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:01:50.720 --> 01:01:53.360 align:middle line:90%
So how big is that?

01:01:53.360 --> 01:01:58.360 align:middle line:84%
So f hat of ksi is bounded
by the integral f of x,

01:01:58.360 --> 01:02:02.390 align:middle line:84%
e to the minus 2
pi i x dot ksi dx.

01:02:02.390 --> 01:02:06.710 align:middle line:84%
And the most common approach,
the easiest approach

01:02:06.710 --> 01:02:09.310 align:middle line:84%
is to use the
triangle inequality.

01:02:09.310 --> 01:02:12.670 align:middle line:90%
So we have this.

01:02:12.670 --> 01:02:15.613 align:middle line:90%
So now we have the L1 norm of f.

01:02:15.613 --> 01:02:16.530 align:middle line:90%
So we have two pieces.

01:02:16.530 --> 01:02:18.450 align:middle line:84%
One piece is controlled
by the L2 norm of f.

01:02:18.450 --> 01:02:22.550 align:middle line:84%
The other piece is controlled
by the L1 norm of f.

01:02:22.550 --> 01:02:24.710 align:middle line:84%
I could have written
the theorem that way,

01:02:24.710 --> 01:02:26.450 align:middle line:84%
but I wrote it a
little bit differently.

01:02:26.450 --> 01:02:27.990 align:middle line:90%
I thought it was cuter.

01:02:27.990 --> 01:02:30.663 align:middle line:84%
I had the support of
f is in the unit ball.

01:02:30.663 --> 01:02:32.330 align:middle line:84%
If the support of f
is in the unit ball,

01:02:32.330 --> 01:02:35.910 align:middle line:84%
then we can control the
L1 norm by the L2 norm.

01:02:35.910 --> 01:02:41.630 align:middle line:84%
So since the support of
f is in the unit ball,

01:02:41.630 --> 01:02:47.430 align:middle line:84%
integral of f of x
dx looks like that.

01:02:47.430 --> 01:02:53.190 align:middle line:84%
It's bounded by the integral of
f of x squared to the 1/2 times

01:02:53.190 --> 01:02:56.910 align:middle line:84%
the integral over the
unit ball of 1 to the 1/2.

01:02:56.910 --> 01:02:58.540 align:middle line:90%
So that's bounded by f L2.

01:02:58.540 --> 01:03:01.100 align:middle line:90%


01:03:01.100 --> 01:03:02.700 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:03:02.700 --> 01:03:08.570 align:middle line:84%
Using the support, I can bound
both 1 and 2 by f L2 squared.

01:03:08.570 --> 01:03:12.980 align:middle line:90%


01:03:12.980 --> 01:03:14.232 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:03:14.232 --> 01:03:18.780 align:middle line:84%
That was what I had thought of
as the proof of the theorem.

01:03:18.780 --> 01:03:20.380 align:middle line:84%
But now is a good
moment to come back

01:03:20.380 --> 01:03:22.420 align:middle line:84%
to the question that
was asked earlier.

01:03:22.420 --> 01:03:24.980 align:middle line:84%
What do you actually have to
assume about f for all of this

01:03:24.980 --> 01:03:25.590 align:middle line:90%
to make sense?

01:03:25.590 --> 01:03:28.260 align:middle line:90%


01:03:28.260 --> 01:03:29.820 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:03:29.820 --> 01:03:34.970 align:middle line:84%
So let me add some fine print,
write what we actually proved.

01:03:34.970 --> 01:03:43.180 align:middle line:90%


01:03:43.180 --> 01:03:43.800 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:03:43.800 --> 01:03:47.580 align:middle line:84%
So the fine print is
for the time being,

01:03:47.580 --> 01:03:51.260 align:middle line:84%
suppose that f is
a Schwarz function.

01:03:51.260 --> 01:03:52.860 align:middle line:84%
We needed f as a
Schwarz function

01:03:52.860 --> 01:03:55.380 align:middle line:84%
to justify our formula
about the Fourier

01:03:55.380 --> 01:03:58.260 align:middle line:84%
transform of the projection,
and in a few other places

01:03:58.260 --> 01:04:01.490 align:middle line:84%
to make sure all these
Fourier transforms make sense.

01:04:01.490 --> 01:04:04.970 align:middle line:84%
If you assume that f is Schwarz,
everything we wrote makes sense

01:04:04.970 --> 01:04:08.090 align:middle line:90%
and we get this estimate.

01:04:08.090 --> 01:04:11.610 align:middle line:90%
And this is an inequality.

01:04:11.610 --> 01:04:14.550 align:middle line:84%
And then it is now possible
to do some extra work.

01:04:14.550 --> 01:04:16.530 align:middle line:84%
If you have a function
that's not Schwarz, just

01:04:16.530 --> 01:04:19.690 align:middle line:84%
a function in L2, you could have
a sequence of Schwarz functions

01:04:19.690 --> 01:04:23.080 align:middle line:90%
that approximate it.

01:04:23.080 --> 01:04:25.590 align:middle line:84%
And for each one of those
approximating functions,

01:04:25.590 --> 01:04:26.913 align:middle line:90%
this bound would be true.

01:04:26.913 --> 01:04:28.330 align:middle line:84%
And then with some
work, you could

01:04:28.330 --> 01:04:31.230 align:middle line:84%
show that the bound is also true
for the limiting function f.

01:04:31.230 --> 01:04:36.290 align:middle line:90%


01:04:36.290 --> 01:04:36.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:04:36.790 --> 01:04:37.800 align:middle line:90%
So I'll put a remark.

01:04:37.800 --> 01:04:40.770 align:middle line:90%


01:04:40.770 --> 01:04:46.200 align:middle line:84%
Can remove the
hypothesis of f Schwarz.

01:04:46.200 --> 01:05:02.840 align:middle line:90%


01:05:02.840 --> 01:05:03.340 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:03.340 --> 01:05:06.150 align:middle line:90%


01:05:06.150 --> 01:05:08.860 align:middle line:84%
So any questions or comments
about the proof of this theorem?

01:05:08.860 --> 01:05:16.350 align:middle line:90%


01:05:16.350 --> 01:05:19.750 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So it's a condition
that the support of f

01:05:19.750 --> 01:05:23.957 align:middle line:90%
is essential to this theorem?

01:05:23.957 --> 01:05:24.790 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

01:05:24.790 --> 01:05:25.290 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:25.290 --> 01:05:28.710 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, is the
assumption that the support of f

01:05:28.710 --> 01:05:30.610 align:middle line:90%
is in the unit ball essential?

01:05:30.610 --> 01:05:33.270 align:middle line:84%
What would happen if we
removed this assumption?

01:05:33.270 --> 01:05:33.830 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:05:33.830 --> 01:05:35.920 align:middle line:84%
So looking at the
proof, we could--

01:05:35.920 --> 01:05:38.470 align:middle line:90%


01:05:38.470 --> 01:05:39.520 align:middle line:90%
let me get another color.

01:05:39.520 --> 01:05:48.310 align:middle line:90%


01:05:48.310 --> 01:05:50.550 align:middle line:84%
Looking at the proof,
we could, if we want to,

01:05:50.550 --> 01:05:52.070 align:middle line:90%
remove this assumption.

01:05:52.070 --> 01:05:55.940 align:middle line:84%
And then we would need to
add the L1 norm, as well

01:05:55.940 --> 01:05:58.880 align:middle line:90%
as the L2 norm to deal with.

01:05:58.880 --> 01:06:01.660 align:middle line:90%


01:06:01.660 --> 01:06:04.240 align:middle line:84%
Due to my brilliant
neighbor labeling scheme,

01:06:04.240 --> 01:06:06.260 align:middle line:84%
term one is bounded
by the L2 norm

01:06:06.260 --> 01:06:08.480 align:middle line:84%
and term two is
bounded by the L1 norm.

01:06:08.480 --> 01:06:11.260 align:middle line:90%


01:06:11.260 --> 01:06:12.460 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:06:12.460 --> 01:06:14.500 align:middle line:84%
I haven't thought
about it carefully.

01:06:14.500 --> 01:06:18.900 align:middle line:84%
You could ask if we did
this, would it still be true?

01:06:18.900 --> 01:06:22.660 align:middle line:84%
I suspect that's not true, and
the natural example to look at

01:06:22.660 --> 01:06:25.880 align:middle line:84%
is a function on
a really big ball.

01:06:25.880 --> 01:06:27.660 align:middle line:84%
I haven't thought it
through carefully.

01:06:27.660 --> 01:06:31.330 align:middle line:84%
It's a good little project
to figure out what happens.

01:06:31.330 --> 01:06:48.340 align:middle line:90%


01:06:48.340 --> 01:06:50.100 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:06:50.100 --> 01:06:50.600 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:06:50.600 --> 01:06:53.930 align:middle line:84%
So the big picture
takeaway of this theorem

01:06:53.930 --> 01:06:56.450 align:middle line:84%
is we take a function in
high dimensions, which is not

01:06:56.450 --> 01:07:00.230 align:middle line:84%
very regular, and when we
project it to low dimensions,

01:07:00.230 --> 01:07:03.250 align:middle line:84%
most of the projections
are much more regular.

01:07:03.250 --> 01:07:05.483 align:middle line:84%
And I was trying
to think of places

01:07:05.483 --> 01:07:07.650 align:middle line:84%
that this relates to or we
might have seen something

01:07:07.650 --> 01:07:09.690 align:middle line:90%
like this before.

01:07:09.690 --> 01:07:12.770 align:middle line:84%
And one place where we
see something like this

01:07:12.770 --> 01:07:15.150 align:middle line:84%
is the central limit
theorem in probability.

01:07:15.150 --> 01:07:17.770 align:middle line:90%


01:07:17.770 --> 01:07:19.860 align:middle line:84%
So let me remind
us how that works.

01:07:19.860 --> 01:07:49.370 align:middle line:90%


01:07:49.370 --> 01:07:50.324 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:07:50.324 --> 01:07:58.280 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that Xj are random
variables which are uniformly

01:07:58.280 --> 01:08:06.260 align:middle line:84%
distributed in 0, 1 and there
are a lot of them going up to n.

01:08:06.260 --> 01:08:08.840 align:middle line:90%


01:08:08.840 --> 01:08:09.560 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:08:09.560 --> 01:08:11.080 align:middle line:84%
So in the central
limit theorem, we

01:08:11.080 --> 01:08:13.000 align:middle line:84%
might think what
happens if we add up

01:08:13.000 --> 01:08:16.800 align:middle line:90%
all these random variables.

01:08:16.800 --> 01:08:20.840 align:middle line:84%
So then we could look
at the sum of the Xj.

01:08:20.840 --> 01:08:24.080 align:middle line:90%
This will be a random variable.

01:08:24.080 --> 01:08:26.260 align:middle line:84%
Actually, let me put
it-- not that important.

01:08:26.260 --> 01:08:29.100 align:middle line:84%
But I'm going to
put minus 1/2, 1/2.

01:08:29.100 --> 01:08:31.100 align:middle line:84%
The central limit theorem
is a little bit nicer.

01:08:31.100 --> 01:08:34.159 align:middle line:90%


01:08:34.159 --> 01:08:34.659 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:08:34.659 --> 01:08:37.600 align:middle line:84%
So what happens
when I add them up?

01:08:37.600 --> 01:08:43.200 align:middle line:84%
When I add them up, the
central limit theorem

01:08:43.200 --> 01:08:47.560 align:middle line:84%
says that the sum of
these random variables

01:08:47.560 --> 01:08:54.819 align:middle line:84%
is approximately a
Gaussian with mean 0

01:08:54.819 --> 01:09:00.160 align:middle line:84%
and a standard deviation,
something like square root of n.

01:09:00.160 --> 01:09:04.380 align:middle line:90%


01:09:04.380 --> 01:09:08.550 align:middle line:84%
And notice in particular
that it's quite smooth.

01:09:08.550 --> 01:09:19.500 align:middle line:90%


01:09:19.500 --> 01:09:20.740 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:20.740 --> 01:09:24.340 align:middle line:84%
So the probability, the joint
probability density function

01:09:24.340 --> 01:09:25.490 align:middle line:90%
of these Xj's.

01:09:25.490 --> 01:09:32.700 align:middle line:90%


01:09:32.700 --> 01:09:34.260 align:middle line:90%
Xj.

01:09:34.260 --> 01:09:38.180 align:middle line:90%
Is f of X1 up to XN.

01:09:38.180 --> 01:09:41.209 align:middle line:84%
So the characteristic
function of the cube.

01:09:41.209 --> 01:09:45.020 align:middle line:90%


01:09:45.020 --> 01:09:46.920 align:middle line:90%
So this is a typical--

01:09:46.920 --> 01:09:48.810 align:middle line:84%
this is an example of
a function that's in L2

01:09:48.810 --> 01:09:51.890 align:middle line:90%
but is not continuous.

01:09:51.890 --> 01:09:53.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:53.130 --> 01:09:59.210 align:middle line:84%
Now what is the probability
density function of this thing?

01:09:59.210 --> 01:10:01.010 align:middle line:90%
Well, we have a map.

01:10:01.010 --> 01:10:05.850 align:middle line:84%
I guess the summation
map goes from RN to R

01:10:05.850 --> 01:10:10.610 align:middle line:84%
and it just takes X1
up to XN and maps it

01:10:10.610 --> 01:10:13.090 align:middle line:84%
to X1 plus dot,
dot, dot plus XN.

01:10:13.090 --> 01:10:13.790 align:middle line:90%
Add them up.

01:10:13.790 --> 01:10:15.970 align:middle line:90%
It's a linear map.

01:10:15.970 --> 01:10:22.530 align:middle line:84%
So the probability
density function

01:10:22.530 --> 01:10:33.210 align:middle line:84%
of the sum of the Xj's is
the pushforward of f dx.

01:10:33.210 --> 01:10:35.630 align:middle line:84%
And this is a slightly
different language,

01:10:35.630 --> 01:10:38.910 align:middle line:84%
but up to a small
change of variables,

01:10:38.910 --> 01:10:42.220 align:middle line:84%
it's the projection of
f on the main diagonal.

01:10:42.220 --> 01:10:46.600 align:middle line:90%


01:10:46.600 --> 01:10:53.760 align:middle line:84%
So actually, we can
make this look nicer

01:10:53.760 --> 01:10:58.360 align:middle line:84%
if we normalize in the central
limit theorem, which is a fairly

01:10:58.360 --> 01:10:59.740 align:middle line:90%
standard way of writing it.

01:10:59.740 --> 01:11:02.060 align:middle line:84%
So let me write the central
limit theorem this way.

01:11:02.060 --> 01:11:06.880 align:middle line:90%


01:11:06.880 --> 01:11:15.080 align:middle line:90%
So now my function is that.

01:11:15.080 --> 01:11:22.920 align:middle line:84%
And let's say that theta is
1 over square root of N 1, 1,

01:11:22.920 --> 01:11:24.560 align:middle line:90%
which is a unit vector.

01:11:24.560 --> 01:11:26.920 align:middle line:90%
So this is just the projection.

01:11:26.920 --> 01:11:30.060 align:middle line:84%
I'll call it theta 1 in
the theta 1 direction of f.

01:11:30.060 --> 01:11:33.720 align:middle line:90%


01:11:33.720 --> 01:11:39.080 align:middle line:84%
So I take the characteristic
function of the cube.

01:11:39.080 --> 01:11:42.280 align:middle line:84%
If I project it
in that direction,

01:11:42.280 --> 01:11:45.150 align:middle line:84%
I get something that
is almost a Gaussian.

01:11:45.150 --> 01:11:48.830 align:middle line:84%
And that's the
central limit theorem.

01:11:48.830 --> 01:11:52.740 align:middle line:84%
And notice in particular that
that projection is quite smooth.

01:11:52.740 --> 01:11:55.790 align:middle line:90%


01:11:55.790 --> 01:11:57.870 align:middle line:84%
So if I were to take
the cube and I were just

01:11:57.870 --> 01:12:01.190 align:middle line:84%
going to project it
onto the x1 axis,

01:12:01.190 --> 01:12:03.750 align:middle line:84%
well, the other variables
would be irrelevant.

01:12:03.750 --> 01:12:05.750 align:middle line:84%
And I would just get the
characteristic function

01:12:05.750 --> 01:12:06.830 align:middle line:90%
of an interval.

01:12:06.830 --> 01:12:09.750 align:middle line:84%
It would not be any
smoother than it was before.

01:12:09.750 --> 01:12:11.537 align:middle line:90%
Still be discontinuous.

01:12:11.537 --> 01:12:12.370 align:middle line:90%
And that's the same.

01:12:12.370 --> 01:12:14.130 align:middle line:84%
I could project it
onto any of the axes.

01:12:14.130 --> 01:12:15.005 align:middle line:90%
They're all the same.

01:12:15.005 --> 01:12:18.270 align:middle line:84%
That would be a characteristic
function of an interval.

01:12:18.270 --> 01:12:21.287 align:middle line:84%
But if I project it
onto the main diagonal,

01:12:21.287 --> 01:12:23.370 align:middle line:84%
then I get the thing in
the central limit theorem,

01:12:23.370 --> 01:12:24.790 align:middle line:90%
which is extremely smooth.

01:12:24.790 --> 01:12:29.350 align:middle line:84%
And the more I
increase the dimension,

01:12:29.350 --> 01:12:30.810 align:middle line:84%
the more it looks
like a Gaussian.

01:12:30.810 --> 01:12:34.630 align:middle line:84%
And in particular,
the smoother it gets.

01:12:34.630 --> 01:12:35.616 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:12:35.616 --> 01:12:37.370 align:middle line:84%
Now in the central
limit theorem,

01:12:37.370 --> 01:12:39.950 align:middle line:84%
it actually is not terribly
important that all of these

01:12:39.950 --> 01:12:41.430 align:middle line:90%
are exactly 1.

01:12:41.430 --> 01:12:46.810 align:middle line:84%
It's just important that they're
roughly equal to each other.

01:12:46.810 --> 01:12:50.050 align:middle line:84%
So as long as you take
a direction, which

01:12:50.050 --> 01:12:53.650 align:middle line:84%
doesn't emphasize any of the
coordinate axes too much,

01:12:53.650 --> 01:12:55.950 align:middle line:84%
you'll see something like
the central limit theorem.

01:12:55.950 --> 01:12:58.090 align:middle line:84%
So in all of those
directions, the projection

01:12:58.090 --> 01:12:59.150 align:middle line:90%
will look quite smooth.

01:12:59.150 --> 01:13:01.150 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, it will look
a lot like a Gaussian.

01:13:01.150 --> 01:13:03.570 align:middle line:90%


01:13:03.570 --> 01:13:05.930 align:middle line:84%
But if you were to project
it in the bad directions,

01:13:05.930 --> 01:13:08.810 align:middle line:84%
in a coordinate direction
or a combination of a couple

01:13:08.810 --> 01:13:10.242 align:middle line:84%
coordinate directions,
then you'll

01:13:10.242 --> 01:13:11.700 align:middle line:84%
get something that's
not so smooth.

01:13:11.700 --> 01:13:14.910 align:middle line:90%


01:13:14.910 --> 01:13:15.410 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:15.410 --> 01:13:18.810 align:middle line:84%
So that's an example
of this theorem.

01:13:18.810 --> 01:13:22.010 align:middle line:84%
And in this special example, we
can say much more refined things

01:13:22.010 --> 01:13:23.770 align:middle line:84%
about which directions
are good and bad

01:13:23.770 --> 01:13:25.890 align:middle line:90%
and exactly what happens.

01:13:25.890 --> 01:13:27.590 align:middle line:84%
But this theorem is
a lot more general,

01:13:27.590 --> 01:13:29.610 align:middle line:84%
because you don't have to put
in the characteristic function

01:13:29.610 --> 01:13:30.430 align:middle line:90%
of a cube.

01:13:30.430 --> 01:13:33.690 align:middle line:84%
You can put in quite a
broad range of functions,

01:13:33.690 --> 01:13:35.900 align:middle line:84%
and qualitatively
similar things happen.

01:13:35.900 --> 01:13:49.890 align:middle line:90%


01:13:49.890 --> 01:13:50.390 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:13:50.390 --> 01:13:52.720 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] but
this theorem and the theorem

01:13:52.720 --> 01:13:55.260 align:middle line:84%
you did earlier,
it's really the same.

01:13:55.260 --> 01:13:56.760 align:middle line:84%
Like when you
integrate, you make

01:13:56.760 --> 01:13:59.800 align:middle line:84%
it smoother because the
production is an integration,

01:13:59.800 --> 01:14:01.168 align:middle line:90%
kind of.

01:14:01.168 --> 01:14:01.960 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yes.

01:14:01.960 --> 01:14:03.860 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

01:14:03.860 --> 01:14:08.360 align:middle line:84%
The comment is that
when we project,

01:14:08.360 --> 01:14:13.120 align:middle line:84%
we project by integrating
some of the variables.

01:14:13.120 --> 01:14:15.560 align:middle line:84%
And so the comment is when
we integrate something

01:14:15.560 --> 01:14:16.732 align:middle line:90%
we make it smoother.

01:14:16.732 --> 01:14:17.940 align:middle line:90%
That's a really nice comment.

01:14:17.940 --> 01:14:22.507 align:middle line:84%
And it reminds us of something
more familiar and fundamental,

01:14:22.507 --> 01:14:24.840 align:middle line:84%
which is like if you had a
function of one variable that

01:14:24.840 --> 01:14:27.903 align:middle line:84%
was just an L2 site or
L1, if you integrated it,

01:14:27.903 --> 01:14:28.820 align:middle line:90%
it would get smoother.

01:14:28.820 --> 01:14:30.653 align:middle line:84%
If you integrated it a
whole bunch of times,

01:14:30.653 --> 01:14:33.020 align:middle line:84%
then you would get
something smooth.

01:14:33.020 --> 01:14:33.520 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:14:33.520 --> 01:14:34.900 align:middle line:90%
So this is a little bit like--

01:14:34.900 --> 01:14:36.260 align:middle line:90%
this is a little bit like that.

01:14:36.260 --> 01:14:40.550 align:middle line:84%
And I guess this smoothness does
come from doing the integration.

01:14:40.550 --> 01:14:42.790 align:middle line:90%
In this situation-- yeah?

01:14:42.790 --> 01:14:43.530 align:middle line:90%
What's that?

01:14:43.530 --> 01:14:45.470 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: The bounds
are interesting still.

01:14:45.470 --> 01:14:47.278 align:middle line:84%
Like how smooth it
is is interesting.

01:14:47.278 --> 01:14:48.070 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yes.

01:14:48.070 --> 01:14:49.250 align:middle line:90%
The bounds are interesting.

01:14:49.250 --> 01:14:49.790 align:middle line:90%
Yes.

01:14:49.790 --> 01:14:50.290 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:14:50.290 --> 01:14:51.707 align:middle line:84%
And I guess one
of the differences

01:14:51.707 --> 01:14:54.450 align:middle line:84%
here is this function
depends on many variables.

01:14:54.450 --> 01:14:58.870 align:middle line:84%
We're going to integrate
some of them but not others.

01:14:58.870 --> 01:15:04.630 align:middle line:90%
And so-- yeah.

01:15:04.630 --> 01:15:05.573 align:middle line:90%
Anyway.

01:15:05.573 --> 01:15:07.990 align:middle line:84%
And then it depends which ones
we integrate whether or not

01:15:07.990 --> 01:15:08.890 align:middle line:90%
it gets smoother.

01:15:08.890 --> 01:15:10.520 align:middle line:84%
But it turns out
that usually it does.

01:15:10.520 --> 01:15:15.950 align:middle line:90%


01:15:15.950 --> 01:15:16.450 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:15:16.450 --> 01:15:19.130 align:middle line:84%
But yeah, I think that is a
good way of looking at it.

01:15:19.130 --> 01:15:21.670 align:middle line:90%


01:15:21.670 --> 01:15:23.270 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:15:23.270 --> 01:15:24.950 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:15:24.950 --> 01:15:25.710 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:15:25.710 --> 01:15:26.250 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:15:26.250 --> 01:15:27.570 align:middle line:90%
So let me end by mentioning.

01:15:27.570 --> 01:15:29.028 align:middle line:84%
So as part of the
class, I will try

01:15:29.028 --> 01:15:32.470 align:middle line:84%
to mention different ways that
projection theory is related

01:15:32.470 --> 01:15:36.150 align:middle line:90%
to various parts of math.

01:15:36.150 --> 01:15:41.180 align:middle line:84%
And so this reminds me of
something I heard about,

01:15:41.180 --> 01:15:44.100 align:middle line:84%
which is about trying to
generalize the central limit

01:15:44.100 --> 01:15:44.980 align:middle line:90%
theorem.

01:15:44.980 --> 01:15:51.000 align:middle line:84%
So what if the input was not
independent random variables,

01:15:51.000 --> 01:15:53.300 align:middle line:84%
but something
somewhat more general?

01:15:53.300 --> 01:15:56.328 align:middle line:84%
Would it still be true that when
we take a projection like this,

01:15:56.328 --> 01:15:57.370 align:middle line:90%
you would see a Gaussian?

01:15:57.370 --> 01:16:01.540 align:middle line:90%


01:16:01.540 --> 01:16:05.460 align:middle line:84%
And so there's a big
body of work on that.

01:16:05.460 --> 01:16:07.700 align:middle line:84%
But one interesting
direction I heard about

01:16:07.700 --> 01:16:11.340 align:middle line:84%
is initiated by Keith
Ball and its connection

01:16:11.340 --> 01:16:14.540 align:middle line:84%
between probability theory
and convex geometry.

01:16:14.540 --> 01:16:16.980 align:middle line:84%
And the point of
view is that maybe

01:16:16.980 --> 01:16:18.700 align:middle line:84%
to some extent,
what's important about

01:16:18.700 --> 01:16:21.620 align:middle line:84%
the cube is just that
it's a convex set.

01:16:21.620 --> 01:16:26.500 align:middle line:84%
So instead of the cube, take
any convex set in R to the N

01:16:26.500 --> 01:16:28.980 align:middle line:90%
and it's large.

01:16:28.980 --> 01:16:29.480 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:29.480 --> 01:16:31.420 align:middle line:84%
Now there's no
distinguished-- there's

01:16:31.420 --> 01:16:34.800 align:middle line:84%
nothing special about the
coordinate axes anymore.

01:16:34.800 --> 01:16:37.640 align:middle line:84%
The coordinate axis projections
aren't necessarily the ones

01:16:37.640 --> 01:16:40.040 align:middle line:84%
that are bad, but this one
isn't necessarily good.

01:16:40.040 --> 01:16:42.840 align:middle line:84%
But the question
he raised is maybe

01:16:42.840 --> 01:16:46.000 align:middle line:84%
you take any convex set
and look at its projections

01:16:46.000 --> 01:16:48.040 align:middle line:90%
onto one dimensional spaces.

01:16:48.040 --> 01:16:50.410 align:middle line:84%
Maybe most of them
are almost Gaussian.

01:16:50.410 --> 01:16:54.366 align:middle line:90%


01:16:54.366 --> 01:16:54.866 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:54.866 --> 01:16:57.020 align:middle line:84%
And that's a recent
topic of research,

01:16:57.020 --> 01:17:00.480 align:middle line:84%
and a significant amount
like that is true.

01:17:00.480 --> 01:17:02.460 align:middle line:84%
Keith Ball gave an
ICM talk about it

01:17:02.460 --> 01:17:04.360 align:middle line:84%
and I put some references
in the homework

01:17:04.360 --> 01:17:06.620 align:middle line:84%
if anybody is interested
in reading about it.

01:17:06.620 --> 01:17:10.080 align:middle line:90%


01:17:10.080 --> 01:17:12.080 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:17:12.080 --> 01:17:12.580 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:12.580 --> 01:17:16.240 align:middle line:84%
Well, let's stop
there for today.

01:17:16.240 --> 01:17:18.000 align:middle line:84%
The plan for Thursday
is to come back

01:17:18.000 --> 01:17:19.500 align:middle line:84%
to the large sieve,
which is done,

01:17:19.500 --> 01:17:20.667 align:middle line:90%
which is from number theory.

01:17:20.667 --> 01:17:23.040 align:middle line:84%
And I'll try to tell you
some things, what kind

01:17:23.040 --> 01:17:27.030 align:middle line:84%
of applications in number theory
does the large sieve have.

01:17:27.030 --> 01:17:34.000 align:middle line:90%